WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.480
[Amit Varma]: The Greek philosopher Heraclitus once said,

00:00:08.480 --> 00:00:13.600
[Amit Varma]: No man ever steps in the same river twice, for it's not the same river and it's not the same man.

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:18.480
[Amit Varma]: I sometimes think back to the person I was in my early 20s and wonder how anyone who knew me then

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:23.200
[Amit Varma]: can still be friends with me. We all change with time and become different. But what is this

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:28.400
[Amit Varma]: difference? To me, it has to do with how we see the world. We come into this world and grow into

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:33.040
[Amit Varma]: this world with a certain vision of it, a way of seeing. This could be shaped by our geography,

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:37.840
[Amit Varma]: our circumstances, our upbringing, and all sorts of accidents. And as we go through life,

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:42.880
[Amit Varma]: this way of seeing changes. Layers of blindness that once stopped us from seeing certain facets

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:47.520
[Amit Varma]: of the world are stripped away. And sometimes we add layers because we want to see the world

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:53.120
[Amit Varma]: in a certain way. Some people can go through life as blind at 80 as ever at 20. And maybe that's

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:58.960
[Amit Varma]: one road to happiness. But if you keep your eyes open, chances are that you will see more and what

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:04.320
[Amit Varma]: you see will change what you are. And there are certain callings which require seeing. If you

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:09.360
[Amit Varma]: are a writer or an artist or a filmmaker or a journalist, your most important faculty is

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:14.720
[Amit Varma]: observation. And that means not just looking at things but seeing them. As my guest on today's

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:24.480
[Amit Varma]: show says, going beyond the facts and searching for the truth. Welcome to the scene and the unseen,

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:29.760
[Unknown]: our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host,

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:38.000
[Amit Varma]: Amit Verma. Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Annie Zaidi, a blogger,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.240
[Amit Varma]: journalist, playwright, filmmaker, and I guess she'd just be happy calling herself a writer.

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:46.880
[Amit Varma]: Annie is written widely about so many subjects that I wasn't sure what I would speak to her

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:52.000
[Amit Varma]: about. In fact, that's why I haven't invited her on the show before. I couldn't pin down any one

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.560
[Amit Varma]: thing that an episode could be about. But I knew that I could have a great conversation with her,

00:01:56.560 --> 00:02:01.600
[Amit Varma]: rambling from one subject to another. I've done discursive episodes like that before which have

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:06.240
[Amit Varma]: turned out to be wonderful, with the likes of Pratap Bhanumata, Paromita Vora, Russ Roberts,

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:12.400
[Amit Varma]: Deepak Shinoi, Rukmini S, and just last week, Raghu Sanjay Lal Jaitley. So I finally stopped procrastinating

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:17.040
[Amit Varma]: and invited Annie to the scene and the unseen. And I'm so glad I did. This turned out to be

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:22.240
[Amit Varma]: such a stimulating conversation. And it isn't even such a ramble. We spoke about many things, yes,

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:27.680
[Amit Varma]: language to politics to religion to art, but without my planning it that way, one larger theme

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:33.440
[Amit Varma]: ran through all of this. How if you combine curiosity with humility, you can see the world

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:39.040
[Amit Varma]: so much more clearly. And the fact that Annie has been so prolific with her fiction, her nonfiction

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:45.600
[Amit Varma]: with plays and short films means that we get to see what she sees and expand our view of the world.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:49.840
[Amit Varma]: If you want to discover her work, I suggest starting with her recent memoir, Bread, Cement,

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:54.720
[Amit Varma]: Cactus. But first, conversation. Before we get there, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

