00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:35.760
[Amit Varma]: Uplevel yourself. Annie, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:41.600
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for having me. I've been wanting to invite you for a long time. And

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:45.840
[Amit Varma]: but what kind of baffled me was that what do we talk about not because there's nothing to talk

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:50.000
[Amit Varma]: about, but because there's so much to talk about in terms of how prolific you have been with the

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of writing that you do, the kind of art that you do, plays as well, films and all of that. And,

00:04:56.240 --> 00:05:00.640
[Amit Varma]: but eventually, I thought that no, you know, should just call Annie on the show and just

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:05.200
[Amit Varma]: try to have a good conversation about anything and everything. But first, let's sort of talk about,

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:09.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, your early days before you came into journalism, like I absolutely

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:15.760
[Amit Varma]: loved your book, Bread, Seam and Cactus. And in the first chapter there, you sort of talk about,

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:21.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, growing up in the town of JK Puram, tell me a little bit about that. And we are broadly the

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:25.920
[Amit Varma]: same age. And, you know, one thread that's kind of been unravelling through a few episodes when

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:32.480
[Amit Varma]: I've had guests of again, around my age, is just sort of talking about how back in those days,

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:36.800
[Amit Varma]: a lot of the things that we take for granted simply weren't there in terms of the internet

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:40.880
[Amit Varma]: and access to all the information in the world and all the knowledge in the world and all of that.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:48.960
[Amit Varma]: So all of us sort of, you know, we consumed the outside world in very piecemeal and random ways,

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:53.680
[Amit Varma]: and those piecemeal and random ways could shape us. And otherwise, we were kind of shaped only

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:59.520
[Amit Varma]: by our immediate sort of geographical location. So, you know, tell me a bit about your childhood,

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:02.640
[Amit Varma]: what kind of kid were you? What did you want to be? What did you read? Did you read?

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:09.920
[Guest]: So reading is the one thing I think that I've always done. And I think I also did a kind of

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:15.760
[Guest]: pre-reading. I was talking to my mother last week, and she told me this quite recently.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:21.440
[Guest]: I still remember some nursery rhymes from my childhood, particularly Hindi nursery rhymes.

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:28.880
[Guest]: I had them by heart. And everybody in the family used to kind of tease me about me going on,

00:06:28.880 --> 00:06:34.320
[Guest]: you know, walking around the house reciting nursery rhymes, etc. These were not nursery

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:38.480
[Guest]: rhymes that were from my own books. These were from my older brother's books. He's

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:46.080
[Guest]: three or four years ahead in the academic way. And when I was two years old, maybe two or two

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:52.080
[Guest]: and a half, I hadn't quite learned to read. But my mother tells me that I had the rhymes by heart.

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:57.360
[Guest]: And I wasn't yet going to school, but my brother was. And there was this book, this book of Hindi

00:06:57.360 --> 00:07:01.840
[Guest]: rhymes. And every time he left the house with it, she says I used to look really anxious.

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:07.200
[Guest]: Not so much that he's leaving, but that the book is leaving. Is this book going to come back?

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:16.480
[Guest]: I think the word and particularly the written word and literature in some form has been there

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:23.840
[Guest]: in my life from the beginning. This is the one thing that hasn't changed at all. That aside,

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:28.560
[Guest]: I think the other thing in our household was that because my grandfather was a writer

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:34.480
[Guest]: and he invested quite heavily in education and literature and culture for his children,

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:41.200
[Guest]: he couldn't afford a lot. The one thing he would not compromise on was education. So he,

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:47.040
[Guest]: as to the extent that he was able, he sent them to the whatever was considered the best schools.

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:57.920
[Guest]: And he did not stint on books. So, for example, when once in his life, I think all his children

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:02.800
[Guest]: were grown up by that time. My mother was already married by that time. But once in his life,

00:08:02.800 --> 00:08:08.080
[Guest]: he got a chance to go to the United States and he kind of traveled widely, came back and

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:13.040
[Guest]: he didn't come back with clothes. He came back with a trunk full of books.

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:17.680
[Guest]: And I remember reading those books and seeing those books and they're like

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:24.960
[Guest]: the maroon leather binding. And I think that was the kind of family and household I was growing up

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:30.320
[Guest]: in. And there was no question of you being denied things to read. As long as people could afford it,

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:35.600
[Guest]: you had it. When we moved to JK Puram, though, it was slightly different.

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:41.680
[Guest]: This is a way out place, as I describe in my memoir. My mother was looking for jobs,

00:08:41.680 --> 00:08:46.640
[Guest]: and the kind of best job that she could find at the time was in an industrial township.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:52.000
[Guest]: Anyone in India who's grown up in an industrial township kind of knows it. There's a template

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.960
[Guest]: to it. You know, they're called, quote unquote, colony. And it is usually near some kind of

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:02.960
[Guest]: natural resource. So in our case, it was near limestone deposits in the hills,

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:07.280
[Guest]: with other factories, it is something else, you know, coal deposits or, you know,

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:14.800
[Guest]: for steel plants and things like that. For us, it was the Aravalli range in Rajasthan. And Rajasthan

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:19.440
[Guest]: is one of those states that has the most number of cement factories because that's where the

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:24.400
[Guest]: limestone is. So we moved there and there was a little school there because there were so few

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:30.240
[Guest]: facilities. I think, I believe there was some kind of primary school, a government school in the

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:35.840
[Guest]: village nearby. But otherwise, for employees, there was nowhere else they could go. So this is

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:44.160
[Guest]: an attempt to set up a private school, which was by the company and for the employees, exclusively

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:53.120
[Guest]: for the employees of that company, the factory. So that's where, from the first onwards, I had

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:57.600
[Guest]: been to kindergarten and other places, but I think from the first standard to the 11th standard,

00:09:57.600 --> 00:10:02.400
[Guest]: to the 11th standard, that's where I went. My mother worked in that school, initially as vice

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:07.680
[Guest]: principal, then as principal. She didn't really teach me though. She taught my brother a little

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:15.200
[Guest]: bit, but not me. She had administrative duties, etc. And she was very, in some ways, a very

00:10:16.480 --> 00:10:22.480
[Guest]: lenient parent, but also a very, how should I say, for instance, she was concerned about

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:27.920
[Guest]: academics because she had to be, that was her job. But for everyone in the family, she wouldn't be

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:36.080
[Guest]: concerned only about me. So she wouldn't teach just me. And this just almost never changed.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:43.760
[Guest]: It was only once when I was failing quite badly in math, because we couldn't find appropriate math

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:50.000
[Guest]: tutors in that little place. And she wasn't a math tutor herself. So she had to read math and then

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:56.240
[Guest]: try and teach me whatever she could understand. But except for, I think, that one month in my

00:10:56.240 --> 00:11:01.040
[Guest]: entire 11 years, she did not teach me at all. She did not teach me English literature. She did not

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:05.680
[Guest]: teach me the social sciences. She kind of left it that, you know, okay, this is the school I run,

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:12.320
[Guest]: and she will learn what everyone else reads and learns. But I read a lot. And I read everything

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:16.480
[Guest]: I could lay my hands on, which wasn't a lot, because this place where I was growing up,

00:11:16.480 --> 00:11:27.520
[Guest]: it had one ration ki dukan, one sabzi ki dukan, one kind of, I think, very small little things

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:37.040
[Guest]: where you could get pins and socks and just cool stuff. You couldn't, one halwai shop,

00:11:37.040 --> 00:11:42.640
[Guest]: that I remember, it had one halwai shop, and nothing else. You couldn't buy your books there,

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:47.440
[Guest]: you couldn't buy birthday cakes there. You couldn't, you certainly couldn't buy anything

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:53.200
[Guest]: that you wanted to read for pleasure. So my earliest memories of reading for pleasure are

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:57.200
[Guest]: when we used to go for the summer holidays. We would go, and there was this railway station,

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:04.320
[Guest]: and you had to kind of sign a requisition form, requisition a cab, and then that cab would take

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:09.120
[Guest]: you to the station. And while we were waiting for the trains, there was a wheeler stall there.

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:16.720
[Guest]: And we were allowed, for a journey, we were allowed one book each. So that was such an

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:23.040
[Guest]: exciting thing, one, to see the stall, to just see this bhandar of books, which I was just

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:29.200
[Guest]: completely obsessed by the fact that they were books and you could buy them, and that I could

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:34.400
[Guest]: choose one. So a lot of time was just spent choosing things. My brother was allowed one,

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:41.200
[Guest]: I was allowed one. And I obviously read too fast, and the journey was much longer. So the book would

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:44.800
[Guest]: be done in maybe three or four hours, and my brother and I would exchange books, and then

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:49.520
[Guest]: that would be finished too. And the rest of the journey, I would just be staring at my mom and,

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:55.680
[Guest]: you know, mom, I'm bored, mom, I'm bored, mom, I'm bored. This was my refrain through all journeys

00:12:56.400 --> 00:13:02.640
[Guest]: for, as I think, for the longest time. But I was never allowed more than one book or one magazine

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:09.360
[Guest]: in all those years. However, my mom was responsible for stocking the library. So

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:14.560
[Guest]: once a year, she would go out and buy 30 books, 50 books, whatever she was allowed,

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:19.840
[Guest]: she was given a budget. And that was my reading growing up. And I would borrow what I could

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:25.680
[Guest]: from other people, uncles, aunties, friends, whatever I could borrow. Otherwise, it was a

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:30.640
[Guest]: very small life, a very limited life, because the kind of place that it was, and because there was

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:35.520
[Guest]: no public transport, and we didn't have our own transport, we didn't have a car, and I certainly

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:40.640
[Guest]: didn't know how to drive. And there's nowhere to go. I mean, even now, I have revisited the place.

00:13:41.360 --> 00:13:46.960
[Guest]: I went back and some old teachers are still there, some of the older teachers and some of the

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:55.920
[Guest]: schoolmates. And there's nowhere to go. You can drive out in either direction for maybe 15,

00:13:55.920 --> 00:14:00.160
[Guest]: 20 minutes, you might come upon a dhaba, you can eat there, but there's nothing else to do. There

00:14:00.160 --> 00:14:06.400
[Guest]: are no clubs, there are no, except for the school itself, there are no libraries, there are no

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:14.960
[Guest]: cinemas within that little place. So that was the kind of upbringing where books were your only

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:19.760
[Guest]: entertainment and escape into anything. And you mentioned that your grandfather,

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:24.480
[Amit Varma]: of course, had written this memoir called Gubare Karwan. Did you read that when you were a kid? Or

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:31.040
[Amit Varma]: did you read that later? What impression did it make on you? Much later, much later, I knew nothing

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:37.840
[Guest]: of my grandfather's work. Plus, it was in Urdu, and it hasn't been translated. And I came to Urdu

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:44.080
[Guest]: very late in my life. When I began to research this question of identity and belonging, and

00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:49.040
[Guest]: a little bit of whatever I remembered from what my grandfather told me, I grew interested. And

00:14:49.040 --> 00:14:55.840
[Guest]: then I dug up this memoir and I began to read it. Even then, I really struggled, I needed help to

00:14:55.840 --> 00:15:01.840
[Guest]: transcribe it, because the lettering is old fashioned. I mean, now with Urdu, if you have

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:06.800
[Guest]: modern fonts, which are a little more clear, but if things were handwritten and typeset in the old

00:15:06.800 --> 00:15:12.720
[Guest]: way, it's really confusing. So I always need to cross check with someone who knows the language

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:16.960
[Guest]: better to kind of send them snapshots and say, am I reading this correct? Is this correct? What is

00:15:16.960 --> 00:15:23.200
[Guest]: this word? It's difficult. I knew very little about my grandfather. My grandfather was a very busy man.

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:27.680
[Guest]: He worked, of course, and even after retirement, he took up a post-retirement position,

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:34.960
[Guest]: and he had his own writing and things. So he used to get up at maybe five in the morning

00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:38.640
[Guest]: and write for about three hours before he went to work, before he went to office.

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:43.920
[Guest]: And then he used to come back and used to have a cup of tea and maybe a little bit of

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:47.600
[Guest]: conversation. And then he used to write again for three hours in the evening,

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:55.680
[Guest]: and then it was dinner and bedtime. So the kind of, I mean, I regret not having those

00:15:55.680 --> 00:16:00.080
[Guest]: conversations with him while I could, you know, the long lengthy conversations about

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:05.200
[Guest]: where we're from, his ideas about politics, but I could never have that because he was

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:08.160
[Guest]: busy creating the literature, I suppose.

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:13.360
[Amit Varma]: And was that aspirational to you in some way, having someone like that in your family who

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:19.680
[Amit Varma]: was a learned man of letters, who was writing, you know, at that point in time, did you,

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:22.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, think of the world in terms of, look, I like to read, I'd also like to write,

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:28.480
[Amit Varma]: or is that something that really happened much later? How did you see yourself in those days?

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:33.600
[Guest]: I don't think I grew up with any sense of wanting to be a writer. I didn't know what

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: I wanted to be. I would keep changing my answer when people asked. I mean, I hated it when

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:44.880
[Guest]: people asked, what do you want to be when you grow up? I suppose like all kids, I cast

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:48.720
[Guest]: around for what other people were saying. So if somebody said doctor, I would also say

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:54.800
[Guest]: doctor. No intention ever of actually being a doctor. Then for a while I figured out,

00:16:54.800 --> 00:17:00.240
[Guest]: okay, science is not my thing. So what can I do? Then I would say I want to be an IS

00:17:00.240 --> 00:17:05.600
[Guest]: officer and everybody would be mighty pleased. Ah, that's what she'd be. But I had no intention

00:17:05.600 --> 00:17:10.480
[Guest]: of being an IS officer either. I was very confused about what I wanted to do for the

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:18.240
[Guest]: longest time. By the time I was in my ninth or 10th though, I think one thing was clear

00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:22.800
[Guest]: to me so that I wanted to do something around literature, English literature. I knew I wanted

00:17:22.800 --> 00:17:28.560
[Guest]: to study English literature. I still continued to study science rather than literature in

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:36.400
[Guest]: my higher secondary, mostly I think circumstances and that's how it was. But I think I knew,

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:41.840
[Guest]: my family also knew that my main strength lay in letters and words. I was very confused

00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:50.480
[Guest]: about what to do, like for a career. I remember in my, was it 10th or 12th, one of these times,

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:56.640
[Guest]: I was sent off to, maybe my 12th, I think, after my 12th, I was sent off to live with

00:17:56.640 --> 00:18:01.760
[Guest]: my grandparents for the summer vacation for maybe a month or two months. And I remember

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:08.320
[Guest]: going to Lucknow, it was just me and the two of them. And my grandfather would be busy

00:18:08.320 --> 00:18:15.520
[Guest]: reading, writing as was his, you know, his thing. I didn't know what to do with myself.

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:20.400
[Guest]: And there was this question of what will you do later? And with literature, I knew that

00:18:20.400 --> 00:18:24.640
[Guest]: there's one thing you can do, which is teaching. And apart from teaching, you have no options

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: in life and I did not want to be a teacher. So what else could I do? I began to sit down

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:34.480
[Guest]: and make lists of, okay, what are my skills? And I realized I have no actual skills.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:39.840
[Guest]: So my grandfather had an old typewriter and I thought, okay, let me learn to type. Kuch

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:44.960
[Guest]: nahi toh I can be a typist or a secretary at least. So I taught myself to type then

00:18:44.960 --> 00:18:49.040
[Guest]: on that old typewriter and used to copy some of his letters and poems just for practice

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:55.280
[Guest]: and things. I remember doing that. But even then, no sense of writing originally. I was

00:18:55.280 --> 00:19:01.360
[Guest]: just copying stuff. I was not writing. I did write essays for school, et cetera, but more

00:19:01.360 --> 00:19:09.600
[Guest]: as an extracurricular activity, not as something I felt I was committed to. In college too,

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:15.280
[Guest]: I had no sense until I think the end of my first year when I discovered that maybe I

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:22.400
[Guest]: could write a little poetry. You enter these little competitions. I entered one of these

00:19:22.400 --> 00:19:28.240
[Guest]: impromptu competitions and then for the first time I wrote something original. And I think

00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:36.480
[Guest]: just by fluke, I think I won a prize because it was just girls of my age. It's not like

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:43.680
[Guest]: you're competing against, all of us are just starting out. But when that happened, I also

00:19:43.680 --> 00:19:49.040
[Guest]: discovered that, okay, there is self-expression here and that I can do this, that this is

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:54.160
[Guest]: something that taps into some part of me, not as a career. I wasn't even thinking of

00:19:54.160 --> 00:20:00.640
[Guest]: that. I was just thinking that, okay, this is something I have a certain affinity for.

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:06.560
[Guest]: I read and maybe I can write. And then I started writing poems and short stories, et cetera.

00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:12.640
[Guest]: Again, not thinking of it as a career, just thinking of it as, you know, okay, let's try

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:19.040
[Guest]: this sort of thing. I remained confused about being a writer, I think, until after I graduated

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:24.720
[Guest]: and I started studying journalism, at which point I think finally I then understood that,

00:20:24.720 --> 00:20:26.800
[Guest]: okay, writing is my thing.

00:20:28.160 --> 00:20:33.680
[Amit Varma]: And so a dual question, one is that in those, you know, teenage years, so to say, or as

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:38.400
[Amit Varma]: a child, or who were the writers of the books that you really liked, that you really enjoyed?

00:20:38.400 --> 00:20:43.440
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, I think in the life of a writer, there comes a point where, because they get

00:20:43.440 --> 00:20:48.080
[Amit Varma]: so involved with writing and language, they become mindful of the writing of others, the

00:20:48.080 --> 00:20:51.280
[Amit Varma]: tricks that others are using, what they are doing with the language, the rhythms they

00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:53.040
[Amit Varma]: are creating, so on and so forth.

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:58.720
[Amit Varma]: And what was that shift like for you? Was it a very gradual process? Or was there like

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:02.400
[Amit Varma]: Arundhati Roy, when she wrote God a Small Thing, said that it was when she started writing

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:06.640
[Amit Varma]: the book that her quality of her reading just went up, which is a phrase that struck with

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:11.280
[Amit Varma]: me the quality of reading. So what was that shift like? And then who were the kind of

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:16.640
[Amit Varma]: writers you began to look up to not just for what they wrote about in thematic terms, but

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:18.800
[Amit Varma]: also the craft and how they did what they did?

00:21:20.320 --> 00:21:26.080
[Guest]: I think actually, I started thinking about craft very late, like very late, given that

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:30.800
[Guest]: I used to read so much. But I think part of the reason was that I used to read at breakneck

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:40.080
[Guest]: speed. I used to reread when I ran out of reading material. So, you know, over the holidays,

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:44.480
[Guest]: I would read in these intense bursts, like I would finish 30 books in two months, 40

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:50.160
[Guest]: books in two months. And then that space, how much time do you have to pick up craft,

00:21:50.160 --> 00:21:58.240
[Guest]: right? So I'd read, I remember. However, I did start paying attention to themes. I think

00:21:58.240 --> 00:22:04.480
[Guest]: when I was in around high school, the question of themes, I think, came first and craft later.

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:14.400
[Guest]: Craft, I think I began to notice only in my late 20s. Because I think even in my own

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:21.840
[Guest]: writing, I started to be a little bit ambitious about writing like in a creative way, in my

00:22:21.840 --> 00:22:28.640
[Guest]: early 20s. And wanting to be published and all of that wasn't happening, not that quickly,

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:32.560
[Guest]: which was good for me, actually, I think, because now I think back,

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:40.000
[Guest]: I thought I was ready to be published in my early 20s. I tried to pull together a manuscript and

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:45.120
[Guest]: met a few publishers. There were very few publishers at the time, and obviously made

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:53.040
[Guest]: no headway. But I kept writing, I kept writing and kept sort of practicing in a sense. And when

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:58.000
[Guest]: I think back, I was writing extremely mediocre stuff. And if that had got published, I think

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:07.760
[Guest]: I would not have grown much as a writer. But at some point in my mid 20s, I was working as a

00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:16.800
[Guest]: journalist full time, but I joined and I also joined and formed, set up two peer review groups

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:23.040
[Guest]: for writers, for aspiring writers. And what we used to do is we used to meet and read out

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:28.560
[Guest]: our work to each other, and give feedback and things like that. I think that is when a little

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:34.240
[Guest]: bit of attention to craft started to happen, at least the mistakes I was making with my own craft.

00:23:34.240 --> 00:23:39.200
[Guest]: And I mean, you could call them mistakes, or you can just say how other people were responding to

00:23:39.200 --> 00:23:46.560
[Guest]: that. I became more conscious of that. And along with that, I think when I started to read something

00:23:46.560 --> 00:23:51.680
[Guest]: and something would really blow me away. So for example, I remember reading Paul Ester's New York

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:58.560
[Guest]: and just the craft of that. It's so in your face, and it's unavoidable, right? You have to,

00:23:58.560 --> 00:24:03.120
[Guest]: oh Murakami, when you first read Murakami, it's like that, okay, what's he doing here?

00:24:03.120 --> 00:24:07.760
[Guest]: Why is this working, even though it should not work, you know, in a conventional sense.

00:24:09.520 --> 00:24:16.720
[Guest]: That I think happened in my mid to late 20s, when I began to, perhaps I think maybe because

00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:21.360
[Guest]: I was also writing and paying attention to what was working and what wasn't.

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:28.080
[Amit Varma]: And when you sort of think about writing and craft, how much of a difference does it make

00:24:28.080 --> 00:24:32.880
[Amit Varma]: that you're actually imbibing culture in different languages? So it's not just English and English,

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:37.600
[Amit Varma]: it's Urdu, it's Hindustani, as it were, as you know, we'll discuss the languages

00:24:38.640 --> 00:24:42.960
[Amit Varma]: later in this episode. But how much did all of that influence your writing? Because it strikes

00:24:42.960 --> 00:24:49.360
[Amit Varma]: me that all of these languages, in terms of values, in terms of what they sort of, you know,

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:53.680
[Amit Varma]: privilege in the way they are structured, are very different from each other. Something that works in

00:24:53.680 --> 00:24:57.680
[Amit Varma]: Urdu may not work in English and vice versa. Murakami is interesting that you named him

00:24:57.680 --> 00:25:03.840
[Amit Varma]: because he's such a rhythmic musical writer. But at the same time, like so many other Japanese

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:10.080
[Amit Varma]: writers, there's also this, you know, a sparseness to his prose, a simplicity to his prose,

00:25:10.080 --> 00:25:14.480
[Amit Varma]: which might have something to do with the Japanese language itself, that it doesn't,

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:19.680
[Amit Varma]: say value or give space for expressionism in the same way that Urdu or Bengali might.

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:24.320
[Amit Varma]: So all of them kind of bring different things to the table. And that's just language like even in

00:25:24.320 --> 00:25:28.560
[Amit Varma]: terms of storytelling, the sort of traditions that you get, you know, the tradition of the

00:25:28.560 --> 00:25:35.120
[Amit Varma]: American short story is so different from how Indian writers would kind of approach it, you

00:25:35.120 --> 00:25:40.000
[Amit Varma]: know. So what was that process of figuring out all these influences? At what point do you start

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:46.720
[Guest]: consciously thinking about them and all of that? So I think that because Urdu, I was more or less

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:52.320
[Guest]: cut off from Urdu literature. There was, it was in the air in the way that spoken Urdu always is,

00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:58.800
[Guest]: I think, especially in North India. It's just there around you. Hindi, a little bit from

00:25:58.800 --> 00:26:03.920
[Guest]: literature. But I also think that what happened with Hindi was that after primary school, very

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:11.120
[Guest]: quickly, I stopped enjoying. The kind of texts that were prescribed were, I suppose, literary

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:18.720
[Guest]: from the point of view of the people who make syllabi, but it was very difficult. The kind of

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:24.720
[Guest]: language used was heavily Sanskritized, that version of Hindi, and I completely lost interest

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:31.920
[Guest]: in. It was there. We still studied it and analyzed it and passed the exams, I suppose. But I think

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:38.560
[Guest]: in secondary school, I do not have a memory of enjoying it much. I do have a very sharp memory

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:44.400
[Guest]: of this poem. I've never forgotten it, partly because of its simplicity, partly because it was

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:51.360
[Guest]: just so different from the Sanskritized kind of literature, both in its intent and the kind of

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:57.600
[Guest]: morality that Hindi literature seemed to be imbued with, you know, kind of punitive morality.

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:05.600
[Guest]: And it wasn't. It was very refreshing, this poem called Radha Sandarya. It was prescribed on our

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:13.680
[Guest]: school syllabus, but it is not in like what is called Shuddh Hindi. It's not pure Hindi.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:21.200
[Guest]: So the lines go something like this. It compares the beauty of Radha to various things and various

00:27:21.200 --> 00:27:28.960
[Guest]: animals particularly. And it was so striking, the imagery, because one, the imagery itself,

00:27:28.960 --> 00:27:34.720
[Guest]: it comes from, I think, a pre-contemporary era. So it says,

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:41.280
[Guest]: which means the waist, the lion. She has stolen her waist from the lion.

00:27:41.280 --> 00:27:50.640
[Guest]: And gaj ko churaya chaal, which is hati se churaya chaal. And it says kahe kavi beni beni

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:56.880
[Guest]: bayal ki churai leni, which is that she has stolen a hair from the nagin, from the snake.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:02.160
[Guest]: And that imagery was striking, the language was striking. I didn't understand much of this and

00:28:02.160 --> 00:28:09.120
[Guest]: I didn't understand much of that. But I remember very sharply enjoying it and understanding that

00:28:09.120 --> 00:28:13.360
[Guest]: this is the kind of thing that I enjoy reading. And I wish that there was more of it.

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:18.240
[Guest]: And the playfulness of it, you know, the last line is,

00:28:26.480 --> 00:28:32.000
[Guest]: And similarly with English, I remember there was this poem prescribed, not for me,

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.360
[Guest]: but for my brother, because I would, I was always reading three years ahead

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:39.360
[Guest]: when his books arrived for his sessions. I would first finish reading my books,

00:28:39.360 --> 00:28:43.120
[Guest]: then I would finish reading his books for both English and Hindi. And then,

00:28:43.120 --> 00:28:46.160
[Guest]: of course, the year would proceed and you'd have to be taught the same text.

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:51.680
[Guest]: So I think I did have a fairly solid grounding in that way, in at least two languages.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:57.440
[Guest]: Urdu, I think I got more from Hindi films. Hindi films were a huge influence on me,

00:28:57.440 --> 00:29:05.760
[Guest]: even though we didn't have a television for the longest time. But I think at some point,

00:29:05.760 --> 00:29:10.240
[Guest]: we used to, you know, there used to be these people who used to travel through with projectors,

00:29:10.240 --> 00:29:15.600
[Guest]: they would set up this white sheet and they would project the film onto it. And you would just sit

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:21.200
[Guest]: there on a dhari or on a chair, like a folding chair, people would carry out their folding

00:29:21.200 --> 00:29:26.960
[Guest]: chairs and sit and watch the film. So that's how I watched some of my earliest cinemas,

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:33.840
[Guest]: Hindi films. And I remember them very clearly. I learned to memorize the songs. I had a little

00:29:33.840 --> 00:29:38.560
[Guest]: notebook in which I would memorize the Hindi film songs and I would write them down. That was my

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:45.360
[Guest]: time pass. And so I knew that I still know them by heart, all those songs of the 70s and 80s that

00:29:45.360 --> 00:29:49.040
[Guest]: I saw growing up. What's your favorite? Tell us one.

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:58.960
[Guest]: Favorite is hard. You know, there was this cassette, like this magnetic tape cassette

00:29:58.960 --> 00:30:04.800
[Guest]: that we had, which was old Lata songs, like really old ones. And there's this one that I

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:10.400
[Guest]: really like, which is Thandi Hawaayin Laira Ke Aayin, Tum Ho Kahan, something like that,

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:16.160
[Guest]: which I knew all of that by heart also. And also Lata Ke Dard Bhare Ki, all of those.

00:30:16.160 --> 00:30:22.400
[Guest]: I think the poetry there, and I absorbed it without it being taught to me. And that was

00:30:22.400 --> 00:30:28.000
[Guest]: very good for me, I think, because I learned to then enjoy it without being tested on it.

00:30:30.800 --> 00:30:37.600
[Guest]: But that was my only literary influence as far as Urdu was concerned. The mixed inheritance was more,

00:30:37.600 --> 00:30:43.200
[Guest]: I would say Hindi rather than English. I mean, Hindi and English.

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:48.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, I'll quote a paragraph from you from your book, where you've sort of described this

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:53.280
[Amit Varma]: very eloquently, where you say, quote, Hindustani, a colloquial Hindi, which was nearer Urdu was

00:30:53.280 --> 00:30:58.160
[Amit Varma]: indeed my possession. The Sanskrit infused version of Hindi taught in school was a burden I bore

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:02.720
[Amit Varma]: reluctantly. It was as if the syllabus had been designed to test how far the envelope of

00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:07.600
[Amit Varma]: comprehension could be pushed. The Hindi of movies, songs, friends, of contemporary poetry

00:31:07.600 --> 00:31:12.400
[Amit Varma]: and fiction was like a cozy room with a rug on the floor. Official Hindi was more like a

00:31:12.400 --> 00:31:17.520
[Amit Varma]: official Hindi was like sitting on a stone floor on cold winter nights, stop code. And I kind of

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:22.640
[Amit Varma]: loved that. And a lot of this a lot of, you know, how, what was essentially one language, whether

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:27.440
[Amit Varma]: you call it Hindustani, or you call it something else, was, you know, went in these different

00:31:27.440 --> 00:31:34.320
[Amit Varma]: directions because of politics is, is so tragic. And you see the sort of contrived effect of that

00:31:34.320 --> 00:31:39.680
[Amit Varma]: on, you know, the worst of Shuddh Hindi as it were, and as indeed, it would probably have been

00:31:39.680 --> 00:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: taught in the schools. I mean, even I remember some pretty dreary Hindi back in the day, though,

00:31:43.840 --> 00:31:47.840
[Amit Varma]: my listeners will be amused to know, by the way, an aside that in both the 10th and the 12th,

00:31:47.840 --> 00:31:53.600
[Amit Varma]: I got more marks in Hindi than in English. So there you go, power of memorizing big words,

00:31:53.600 --> 00:31:59.120
[Amit Varma]: do not try this in any other language. But tell me a little bit about all of that the sort of

00:31:59.120 --> 00:32:05.360
[Amit Varma]: politics behind language, which has affected not only language, but, you know, all of us,

00:32:05.360 --> 00:32:11.440
[Guest]: essentially. I started thinking about the politics of language only in recent years,

00:32:11.440 --> 00:32:18.880
[Guest]: partly because it has been, I think, perhaps on purpose politicized to this extent. I didn't

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:23.920
[Guest]: think much about not being taught Urdu, for example, I, I just didn't think very much about

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:29.120
[Guest]: it when I was growing up. It was what it was, you took it for granted. I regretted it, though,

00:32:29.840 --> 00:32:34.000
[Guest]: because as I grew more interested in poetry, particularly Urdu poetry,

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:40.720
[Guest]: I wanted to know more. And my grandfather was an Urdu poet. So I would ask my mom to read out

00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:44.320
[Guest]: some of his poems, you know, whatever books we had, I would ask her to read them out,

00:32:44.320 --> 00:32:48.240
[Guest]: and then we would copy them down in Hindi. And then we would write letters to him to say,

00:32:48.240 --> 00:32:53.200
[Guest]: explain this, explain this word, explain this word. And that was my actually earliest

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:58.160
[Guest]: Urdu lessons in school. And I was really interested, but there was no way to do it.

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:04.640
[Guest]: I think, I began to think about the politics, particularly because it became a physical

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:11.840
[Guest]: threat. At some point, there's this reports in the media a few years ago about people were kind of

00:33:11.840 --> 00:33:17.680
[Guest]: being facing hostile reactions in metros and buses if they were seen carrying Urdu literature,

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:25.360
[Guest]: or any Urdu literature being equated with, you know, as something foreign and therefore worthy

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:34.000
[Guest]: of suspicion. And this kind of started to upset me. It really upset me, of course, because not only is,

00:33:35.120 --> 00:33:40.480
[Guest]: I mean, obviously, I have a personal inheritance of Urdu from my family, but that apart,

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:48.400
[Guest]: if any language can be called authentically Indian, it is most definitely Urdu. It was created

00:33:48.400 --> 00:33:55.360
[Guest]: in the heart of India, somewhere between from Punjab down up to the Deccan, that that's where

00:33:55.360 --> 00:34:01.120
[Guest]: it was made. And it's absolutely ridiculous that people know this. You know, everybody studied that

00:34:01.120 --> 00:34:08.080
[Guest]: much in school and everybody knows this. So this otherization, the designation of a language as

00:34:08.080 --> 00:34:16.240
[Guest]: not being from here, or just because other people who are now foreign, just because different people

00:34:16.240 --> 00:34:21.520
[Guest]: who live in different countries also own that language, that you should start to treat it with

00:34:21.520 --> 00:34:27.120
[Guest]: hostility at home, was something that I found quite shocking, actually. But once I started

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:31.840
[Guest]: thinking about that, I also began to think about language and power. And then that took me back to

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:38.800
[Guest]: Jaikipura and where I was growing up. Where I was growing up, a small place, obviously. As I've said,

00:34:38.800 --> 00:34:46.000
[Guest]: everybody who moved to that colony was from somewhere else. Everybody, everybody I knew

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:52.960
[Guest]: had come from, say, Gujarat, from Rajasthan, from other parts of India, wherever. There were Malayali

00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:58.880
[Guest]: students, there were Gujarati students. We had, at some point, a third language requirement. I think

00:34:58.880 --> 00:35:05.520
[Guest]: something about CBSE rules having changed or something. And then the question of what third

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:11.280
[Guest]: language can be taught to us, in addition to English Hindi and Sanskrit. Sanskrit was, of

00:35:11.280 --> 00:35:16.880
[Guest]: course, compulsory. But in addition to that, we needed one more language. So we thought about it,

00:35:16.880 --> 00:35:23.520
[Guest]: and I think it was decided, because Rajasthan's official language is Hindi, it was decided that

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:28.800
[Guest]: we should learn Gujarati, because Gujarat is the nearest other state. So for two years, I did learn

00:35:28.800 --> 00:35:33.600
[Guest]: Gujarati. But the fact is that Rajasthan does have two or three other languages. It doesn't have,

00:35:33.600 --> 00:35:40.960
[Guest]: necessarily, its own distinct script. So, Mewari, Marwari. We were surrounded by villagers with

00:35:40.960 --> 00:35:44.960
[Guest]: whom we could not communicate. Labourers would come and they would go. They would talk in their

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:50.080
[Guest]: own language. It did not strike anyone, because these were not quote-unquote, board languages.

00:35:50.080 --> 00:35:56.960
[Guest]: We were never going to give our official exams in any of those languages. So, we had to learn

00:35:56.960 --> 00:36:02.720
[Guest]: our official exams in Mewari or Marwari. It was just a question of picking up another language.

00:36:03.440 --> 00:36:10.960
[Guest]: But the school and the CBSE system did not see fit to then say, okay, why not a local language,

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:17.120
[Guest]: which is perhaps not designated amongst the, you know, whatever, the 16 or 20 or 25,

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:22.000
[Guest]: whatever languages there were in the constitutional list. Why not one more of those?

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:27.360
[Guest]: And it effectively, what language and its politicization does is that it seals people

00:36:27.360 --> 00:36:33.920
[Guest]: off from each other. This is one of the things that official discourse around languages does.

00:36:33.920 --> 00:36:39.920
[Guest]: It ensures that you actually cannot communicate with people who do not know your language. I mean,

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:43.680
[Guest]: that's fundamental, right? If you want to communicate with someone, you must learn

00:36:43.680 --> 00:36:48.640
[Guest]: their language. So, what you're saying is that people who are schooled in Hindi or whose mother

00:36:48.640 --> 00:36:56.800
[Guest]: tongue is Hindi ought not to then communicate with people whose mother tongue is not Hindi.

00:36:56.800 --> 00:37:03.680
[Guest]: Or alternatively, the people whose mother tongue is not Hindi, if they want to communicate at all,

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:08.000
[Guest]: either with other citizens or with the state, you know, which they must, they don't have an

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:14.720
[Guest]: option but to communicate with the state, must then quit on their own language and develop a

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:20.640
[Guest]: certain facility with another language. These were things I began to think of especially as a journalist

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:25.920
[Guest]: because as I traveled, I found that, you know, there is this kind of general thing which is

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:31.520
[Guest]: told to us and I never questioned it either that, you know, Hindi is the most widely spoken language.

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:35.840
[Guest]: Everybody in India speaks Hindi except for the south and maybe the northeast. Everybody understands

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:42.560
[Guest]: Hindi, etc., etc., etc. Everybody understands Hindi to the extent that if you speak in very

00:37:42.560 --> 00:37:46.560
[Guest]: simple ways, they may kind of understand what you're saying. Doesn't mean they can talk back

00:37:46.560 --> 00:37:52.320
[Guest]: to you in that language or that they can express the nuances of what they want to convey that

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:59.760
[Guest]: language. I was covering at one point various north Indian states, so Punjab for sure but also

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:08.480
[Guest]: Himachal and I traveled a lot to Madhya Pradesh and honestly speaking, if I was not accompanied

00:38:08.480 --> 00:38:13.520
[Guest]: by one other person and I usually was, it could be an NGO worker, could be, sometimes it was a

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:18.080
[Guest]: government person, sometimes it was or it was just somebody from the panchayat whose Hindi was

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:23.360
[Guest]: slightly better than the rest of the community. If I did not have help, I could not have reported at all

00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:29.680
[Guest]: and I think that even so, knowing all this, my reportage was most definitely

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:37.600
[Guest]: restricted and not as good as it should be because what you're basically saying is that,

00:38:37.600 --> 00:38:44.320
[Guest]: one, if you're communicating, for example, if I'm going into a community and I need the help of say

00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:49.760
[Guest]: the Sarpanch or say the two people who are well educated in Hindi, well educated enough to

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:55.280
[Guest]: communicate with me and take me to, you know, the homes of the people whoever I want to speak to

00:38:55.920 --> 00:39:02.000
[Guest]: and if there is somebody who is very marginalized in that community who say does not get along with

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:08.240
[Guest]: the Sarpanch or who will not even know that there's a journalist and she wants to talk to you

00:39:09.120 --> 00:39:14.720
[Guest]: unless other people tell that person and bring that person out to talk to me and interpret for me.

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:21.040
[Guest]: If that does not happen, then who am I reporting? What am I reporting? I'm automatically reporting

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:25.680
[Guest]: from the lens and the perspective of the most privileged people in that community

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:31.440
[Guest]: and I became aware of that increasingly, like I found myself increasingly uncomfortable

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:39.920
[Guest]: because I found that I am not able to speak with the most powerless people wherever I go

00:39:41.200 --> 00:39:47.600
[Guest]: and this is something that if I cannot, the state most certainly cannot or does not even want to.

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:51.680
[Guest]: So how does this work? How does this work in a diverse country where

00:39:51.680 --> 00:39:54.800
[Guest]: not everyone speaks the same language?

00:39:55.920 --> 00:40:02.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, one of the sort of the revelations for me in your book was how language can form almost

00:40:02.640 --> 00:40:07.520
[Amit Varma]: a layer of social hierarchy which is, you know, which is like caste or which is like class and

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:11.360
[Amit Varma]: those are the things we talk about but language does a similar thing and of course at a basic

00:40:11.360 --> 00:40:16.800
[Amit Varma]: level we all know that because of our post-colonial baggage and all of that English has become a

00:40:16.800 --> 00:40:23.040
[Amit Varma]: marker of class and has a place of privilege but you know what your incredible chapter on language

00:40:23.040 --> 00:40:27.520
[Amit Varma]: kind of brought home to me was how it plays across so many of these different languages

00:40:27.520 --> 00:40:35.040
[Amit Varma]: like I'll quote from another part of your book where you speak about how it becomes difficult

00:40:35.040 --> 00:40:39.840
[Amit Varma]: to even interface with the state if your first language is something else and you write quote

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:44.000
[Amit Varma]: it is bewildering even scary to get a notice from the government or the municipality

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:49.360
[Amit Varma]: and not be able to fully comprehend it. These are matters of life and death, being asked for

00:40:49.360 --> 00:40:54.160
[Amit Varma]: proof of citizenship, procurement of land, tax areas, warnings to not venture into the forest

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:59.040
[Amit Varma]: or into the sea, information about free healthcare, supplementary diets, court summons, whoever

00:40:59.040 --> 00:41:04.080
[Amit Varma]: controls language controls everything stop quote and elsewhere in the book you also wrote about

00:41:04.080 --> 00:41:07.920
[Amit Varma]: you know how your grandmother I think would be scared of going to the bank because she wasn't

00:41:07.920 --> 00:41:13.360
[Amit Varma]: familiar with the language in the form she might be you know incredibly natural and at ease in her

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:18.240
[Amit Varma]: own language but that's been given an inferior status so she's fumbling with this form and people

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:23.600
[Amit Varma]: are telling her to hurry up and it just becomes so intimidating and the other learning was that

00:41:23.600 --> 00:41:29.280
[Amit Varma]: when Urdu was adopted as the national language of Pakistan it was actually not a language spoken

00:41:29.280 --> 00:41:33.440
[Amit Varma]: there I mean the first language in all of the Pakistani states were different like in Punjab

00:41:33.440 --> 00:41:39.600
[Amit Varma]: it was Punjabi and whatever and Urdu on the other hand not only originated in India in fact the only

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:44.400
[Amit Varma]: foreign part of its origin might be the Sanskrit influence because Sanskrit came from where Syria

00:41:44.400 --> 00:41:49.200
[Amit Varma]: is today but you know there were riots in Bihar you pointed out when it was once officially

00:41:49.200 --> 00:41:54.560
[Amit Varma]: announced as the second language there and all of that and it's just also incredibly political

00:41:54.560 --> 00:41:59.200
[Amit Varma]: you've also written elsewhere about how once you were wearing a tabiz with Urdu on it and

00:41:59.200 --> 00:42:03.200
[Amit Varma]: you realized while you were interviewing someone in a village that you know oh shit this tabiz is

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:09.440
[Amit Varma]: visible and you hid it and you know which was quite striking to me so is this sort of when do

00:42:09.440 --> 00:42:14.080
[Amit Varma]: you start noticing this stuff because one of the things that struck me about your book and we'll

00:42:14.080 --> 00:42:20.960
[Amit Varma]: discuss many different aspects of it is that while you know it's structured as a sort of a memoir

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:25.040
[Amit Varma]: what you're doing is when you're revisiting all of these places you're also seeing them with a

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:30.720
[Amit Varma]: new lens you know looking at language with a new lens or when you know talking about JK Puram

00:42:30.720 --> 00:42:36.160
[Amit Varma]: about JK Puram where you examine how apt it is that is called a colony because what happened

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:42.160
[Amit Varma]: there is essentially colonization you know though many may not think of it that way and we'll delve

00:42:42.160 --> 00:42:50.000
[Amit Varma]: into that as well but so did these lenses shift gradually over time or when you decided to write

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:55.520
[Amit Varma]: for it was that was that moment of examination a part of when you begin to look at things in a new

00:42:55.520 --> 00:43:04.080
[Guest]: way i think one of the things with me is that i think through writing that i very rarely have

00:43:04.080 --> 00:43:10.640
[Guest]: clear ideas about anything until i get into the writing so with regard to this book in particular

00:43:10.640 --> 00:43:15.440
[Guest]: i had been thinking about some of these things for a while like i've been thinking about questions

00:43:15.440 --> 00:43:21.840
[Guest]: of belonging identity place for a very long time even in in my first book for example

00:43:21.840 --> 00:43:28.800
[Guest]: when my first non-fiction book i have this chapter on questions of identity and when i wrote that i

00:43:28.800 --> 00:43:36.160
[Guest]: was much younger as maybe 15 years ago and it used to really trouble me how in india people are so

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:45.440
[Guest]: kind of unhesitating when it comes to asking you to define yourself and define yourself via either

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:54.400
[Guest]: region or caste or religion so this right out there what's your caste i mean i was so shocked

00:43:54.400 --> 00:44:00.320
[Guest]: when that started to happen when i was out in my home what are you and i would say i'm a journalist

00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:05.120
[Guest]: and they would be like no what are you and and they mean your religion and your caste of course

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:11.920
[Guest]: and i i i used to dodge that question initially just because it made me so uncomfortable and then

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:19.360
[Guest]: just out of a kind of uh zit just you know uh obstinacy that i will not answer that what you're

00:44:19.360 --> 00:44:27.360
[Guest]: going to do i remember in a long conversation in in in a railway waiting room with this other woman

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:32.160
[Guest]: young woman she kept asking me what are you and i kept saying i don't know and she said how can you

00:44:32.160 --> 00:44:37.840
[Guest]: not know and i said my parents never told me and she said but how is that even possible i said it's

00:44:37.840 --> 00:44:43.200
[Guest]: possible i said it's possible so uh this was the sort of thing that i used to get into these

00:44:43.200 --> 00:44:49.840
[Guest]: conversations early is to resist the idea of identities set in stone but over the years i

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:55.520
[Guest]: became more curious about what shapes them what shapes my identity actually if i actually had to

00:44:55.520 --> 00:45:02.080
[Guest]: give an answer say how would i try and answer that and i found myself leaning more towards

00:45:02.080 --> 00:45:10.560
[Guest]: language and what was regional affiliation and by regional i don't necessarily mean uh linguistic i

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:18.640
[Guest]: mean for example when i say regional i don't just mean up i mean eastern up you know i feel no

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:23.920
[Guest]: affiliation for western up and then where does this affiliation from eastern up come from it

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:28.720
[Guest]: comes from birth it comes from inheritance it comes from land it comes from stories have been

00:45:28.720 --> 00:45:35.760
[Guest]: told about where my family comes from etc narratives a lot of affiliation comes from narrative and i

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:44.000
[Guest]: grew interested in that so i think that in the course of writing in the course of researching

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:50.960
[Guest]: things i was just blundering upon these different ideas and the more i struggled with these ideas

00:45:50.960 --> 00:45:56.800
[Guest]: the more certain answers presented themselves or at least one way of interpreting those answers

00:45:56.800 --> 00:46:01.680
[Guest]: and things sort of once you start opening up the chapter on women for example

00:46:03.440 --> 00:46:10.240
[Guest]: was not something i was conceiving of at all i did not want to think of i most definitely identify as

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:15.280
[Guest]: a woman whether or not i identify as anything else there's no escaping that i am a woman and that's

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:24.800
[Guest]: not likely to change but um but i hadn't thought of womanhood itself as being um

00:46:24.800 --> 00:46:31.440
[Guest]: a dislocated or very malleable identity in regional terms or even linguistic and cultural

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:37.760
[Guest]: terms i hadn't thought of it until i began the writing when i sat down and started talking to

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:44.400
[Guest]: people then i figured out that okay other women feel differently from me why do they feel that

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:49.840
[Guest]: ah that's because they're married or because their family backgrounds are different from mine they

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:56.080
[Guest]: don't have the choices that i have so i think that for me particularly at that moment comes when i'm

00:46:56.080 --> 00:47:02.400
[Guest]: in the moment when i've already kind of put myself out there into the question and i'm casting about

00:47:02.400 --> 00:47:09.920
[Guest]: for answers and looking to see what i can gather sometimes these more contentious and difficult

00:47:10.720 --> 00:47:18.160
[Guest]: kind of ways of thinking about a particular topic suggest themselves at that time i very rarely plan

00:47:18.160 --> 00:47:23.440
[Guest]: how i will approach a certain question or answer you've written very eloquently at different parts

00:47:23.440 --> 00:47:29.280
[Amit Varma]: of the book about both identity and uh sort of the notion of home and i'll again quote from

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:33.840
[Amit Varma]: something that you say in one of your later chapters uh where you write quote that i grew

00:47:33.840 --> 00:47:38.080
[Amit Varma]: into womanhood with the feeling of dispossession that i could not articulate is not surprising

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:44.160
[Amit Varma]: after all my body my city even my culture was not my own to inhabit obstinate and argumentative i

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:48.400
[Amit Varma]: was the opposite of most feminine virtues advertised in the matrimonial columns of the

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:54.560
[Amit Varma]: newspapers worse i was afraid that i might actually be persuaded seduce colded into in

00:47:54.560 --> 00:48:01.600
[Amit Varma]: inhabiting those values and surrendering uh my selfhood how much did uh you know and what you

00:48:01.600 --> 00:48:06.000
[Amit Varma]: said about you know sort of uh discovering what you think through writing is again resonant joan

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:10.800
[Amit Varma]: didion once said i don't know what i think until i write it down and you know when i kind of teach

00:48:10.800 --> 00:48:17.120
[Amit Varma]: my writing course i also talk about how it's a two-way process it's not that you know something

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:22.240
[Amit Varma]: and then you write it sometimes writing is a way of knowing and finding out and as much about the

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:32.320
[Amit Varma]: self as otherwise now what i've kind of noticed about say our notions of the self is that a lot

00:48:32.320 --> 00:48:38.320
[Amit Varma]: of it is about peeling away layers that stop us from seeing things like you made a short film

00:48:38.320 --> 00:48:43.280
[Amit Varma]: about the color red about seeing red everywhere and i remember you spoke about that uh in an

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:49.920
[Amit Varma]: interview where you spoke about that how you imagined that mumbai was a city of grays but

00:48:49.920 --> 00:48:53.760
[Amit Varma]: then you went around shooting red and you realized that they were just red everywhere

00:48:53.760 --> 00:48:57.920
[Amit Varma]: and what happened what happened is that your previous lens was a particular kind of lens

00:48:57.920 --> 00:49:03.120
[Amit Varma]: and you added a layer to it or you took away that layer which sort of didn't allow you to see red

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:09.280
[Amit Varma]: and you're seeing red everywhere and that struck me as a beautiful metaphor for how we evolve as

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:13.760
[Amit Varma]: people as well like i think for example for a lot of men there's one layer that never kind of goes

00:49:13.760 --> 00:49:19.760
[Amit Varma]: away where they don't sort of realize uh the experience of women in the sense that you know

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:25.360
[Amit Varma]: if i get into a crowded lift with five men i don't feel anything but obviously when a woman does

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:30.000
[Amit Varma]: there is that added layer of self-awareness if you i can go out for a walk at night without

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:35.440
[Amit Varma]: thinking twice about it but even in a safe city like bombay i would imagine that you know there

00:49:35.440 --> 00:49:41.040
[Amit Varma]: is that layer of alertness that women have that's one layer then they can be kind of layers of caste

00:49:41.040 --> 00:49:44.800
[Amit Varma]: which you peel away layers of privilege you don't realize whether they are your class layers of

00:49:44.800 --> 00:49:51.520
[Amit Varma]: language where just you know being able to speak in english with you know a sarkari person

00:49:51.520 --> 00:49:56.400
[Amit Varma]: automatically kind of in a sense you are saying that hey you know you know i could be someone who

00:49:56.400 --> 00:50:02.000
[Amit Varma]: could have influence and get you into trouble or whatever and over time and most people don't become

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:09.120
[Amit Varma]: aware of these layers and i would imagine that as a writer uh you know you are more likely to

00:50:09.120 --> 00:50:13.280
[Amit Varma]: sort of especially if you're doing the kind of writing that you're doing which goes into the

00:50:13.280 --> 00:50:18.960
[Amit Varma]: territory of personal essays and uh fiction and all of that that you're more likely to kind of

00:50:19.760 --> 00:50:24.480
[Amit Varma]: peel those away so when you when you look at say the young annie the 20 year old annie as it were

00:50:24.480 --> 00:50:30.240
[Amit Varma]: and uh you know you today what do you think are those sort of big moments those big learnings

00:50:30.240 --> 00:50:38.720
[Guest]: the layers that are gone god i was so clueless at 20 just i cannot imagine a more clueless person

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:49.520
[Guest]: at 20 see one thing about me was that um i did not grow up in big cities i did not even grow up in

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:56.080
[Guest]: small cities i grew up in this little way out place and then when i did go to college i went

00:50:56.080 --> 00:51:02.640
[Guest]: to a town a small town which made but i went to a girl's hostel and it was very very strict

00:51:02.640 --> 00:51:08.880
[Guest]: you were not allowed out except once or twice a month and that was for maybe two or three hours

00:51:08.880 --> 00:51:15.600
[Guest]: and that was it and if you stepped out at all even on those once or twice a month occasions

00:51:15.600 --> 00:51:22.400
[Guest]: you need to have a legitimate excuse so you needed to say why you were going out it wasn't enough to

00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:28.240
[Guest]: say i want to go out never you needed to say i'm going to visit my local garden i'm going to visit

00:51:28.240 --> 00:51:35.120
[Guest]: a doctor i'm you know i need to buy some essentials you know i need to buy books i need to

00:51:35.120 --> 00:51:41.200
[Guest]: whatever it was you needed to have a good excuse to do that and because of that my experience of

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:48.240
[Guest]: urban life is extremely limited like even what i knew of Ajmer was next to nothing really i knew

00:51:48.240 --> 00:51:54.240
[Guest]: Lucknow because from family visits and holidays but you obviously are not allowed to go out on

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:58.640
[Guest]: your own then you don't have your own money you don't know how to negotiate public transport so

00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:05.280
[Guest]: you know that that experience is completely different i think when i moved finally to Bombay

00:52:05.280 --> 00:52:15.680
[Guest]: Bombay as it was by that time when i moved back here i the city itself was a very shocking

00:52:15.680 --> 00:52:22.960
[Guest]: experience for one you know just the scale of it the crowds the having to negotiate everything you

00:52:22.960 --> 00:52:28.800
[Guest]: know like it wasn't just that you were negotiating an income you were negotiating every single thing

00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:32.960
[Guest]: negotiating the buses negotiating the trains negotiating the platforms negotiating the

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:38.960
[Guest]: staircases and i think that for the first couple of years all my experience is kind of

00:52:39.760 --> 00:52:47.040
[Guest]: jammed into i cannot separate one strand of experience from the other i do have this one

00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:53.360
[Guest]: very clear memory and this is from when i was younger actually i mentioned one of these

00:52:53.360 --> 00:52:57.360
[Guest]: experiences in the book where when i used to wear shalwar kameez typically in the north when you

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:04.640
[Guest]: wear shalwar kameez you also wear a dupatta and it is not necessarily for the sake of modesty

00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:13.680
[Guest]: it's often just decorative but you know i used to wear it around my neck and i in in bombay's

00:53:14.400 --> 00:53:22.080
[Guest]: local women's compartment the pattas of the dupatta the the the loose ends of the dupatta

00:53:22.080 --> 00:53:28.720
[Guest]: had got trapped between other women and i was trying to get off and the women getting on

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:35.600
[Guest]: and i was almost strangled because you know there was one group of women pushing me out there was

00:53:35.600 --> 00:53:43.040
[Guest]: this became an actual noose around my neck and then i started noticing that nobody wears dupattas

00:53:43.040 --> 00:53:47.600
[Guest]: the women here don't wear things around their neck and then i started to pay close attention

00:53:47.600 --> 00:53:53.840
[Guest]: and i saw that when women get onto the trains get off the trains they often take a scarf or

00:53:53.840 --> 00:53:58.880
[Guest]: dupatta out of their handbags and then they wear them once they're done with the crowds once they're

00:53:58.880 --> 00:54:04.880
[Guest]: sitting in cabs once they're entering the offices that's when they do it and for me that was a

00:54:04.880 --> 00:54:10.960
[Guest]: revelation that oh okay this is how it works these are working women in the fullest sense that you

00:54:10.960 --> 00:54:18.000
[Guest]: know they're not just women who you know can have their home lives but also their external feminine

00:54:18.560 --> 00:54:23.680
[Guest]: selves and they occupy in other towns that was how it worked that you know whatever that

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:32.240
[Guest]: you dressed in in a feminine manner whatever that femininity was and uh you occupied it very fully

00:54:32.240 --> 00:54:38.480
[Guest]: but it wasn't like that in mumbai you constantly negotiated even that because it could become

00:54:38.480 --> 00:54:45.040
[Guest]: something dangerous and these were the little ways in which i began to understand that

00:54:46.160 --> 00:54:54.400
[Guest]: whatever i am whatever i have learned as a child as a young girl as a teenager will have to slowly

00:54:54.400 --> 00:55:01.360
[Guest]: be if not completely given up will have to constantly be tested for context so the problem

00:55:01.360 --> 00:55:06.400
[Guest]: is not the dupatta the problem is the context a crowded train is the context and similarly i found

00:55:06.400 --> 00:55:13.040
[Guest]: that everything else about my life became more and more contextual um growing up as an indian

00:55:13.040 --> 00:55:20.000
[Guest]: middle class child i should say not just woman particularly a girl but you know i mean i think

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:27.680
[Guest]: this applies to men too your ideas morality are so set so fixed going to a police station was

00:55:27.680 --> 00:55:32.400
[Guest]: considered a bad thing because who hangs around in courts and police stations you know people

00:55:32.400 --> 00:55:36.560
[Guest]: who've done wrong things or people who are in trouble and you definitely don't want to be

00:55:36.560 --> 00:55:42.880
[Guest]: somebody who's in trouble so but when i was a journalist once i became a journalist and that

00:55:42.880 --> 00:55:47.280
[Guest]: was my job i had to do it i had to do the rounds of the police stations and the courts and and

00:55:47.280 --> 00:55:55.680
[Guest]: understand that life is so hard for people it is so hard and i had no idea it was this hard

00:55:55.680 --> 00:56:01.920
[Guest]: and i come from a not very privileged background i mean i i was more or less single-parented

00:56:01.920 --> 00:56:06.480
[Guest]: my mother didn't have much money we grew up in these tiny places we didn't have our own vehicles

00:56:06.480 --> 00:56:14.560
[Guest]: all of that i needed a job it wasn't that i was working just fun needed the job but i had no idea

00:56:14.560 --> 00:56:21.440
[Guest]: that life was this hard for so many people i think journalism taught me that and i think that

00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:27.280
[Guest]: introduced me first to to whatever little privilege i had it wasn't a lot it was very

00:56:27.280 --> 00:56:32.880
[Guest]: like we just were barely surviving in the city and i thought that was hard but then you go out

00:56:32.880 --> 00:56:39.600
[Guest]: there then you see that my god life is hard for others you go to public hospitals and you see the

00:56:39.600 --> 00:56:47.360
[Guest]: conditions of those hospitals and i think many of my ideas about not only about what makes people

00:56:47.360 --> 00:56:54.000
[Guest]: do the things they do you know in either a moral sense or just you know in a social sense those

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:59.840
[Guest]: things started to fall away i had grown up with a slight suspicion which i think a lot of kids

00:56:59.840 --> 00:57:06.640
[Guest]: grew up with a slight suspicion of leftist politics even though my grandfather had been

00:57:06.640 --> 00:57:12.080
[Guest]: or at least in his youth for a few years he was socialist and that's in his memoir etc

00:57:13.280 --> 00:57:16.160
[Guest]: but in general around me all conversations were like

00:57:16.160 --> 00:57:24.880
[Guest]: that he is a socialist, he is a communist so you know the the suspicion of ways of thinking

00:57:24.880 --> 00:57:30.560
[Guest]: which were on the left was even without my knowledge i had no idea if you'd ask me as a

00:57:30.560 --> 00:57:35.680
[Guest]: 21 year old what is your politics like i don't know i don't know what left is i don't know what

00:57:35.680 --> 00:57:42.160
[Guest]: right is but once i actually went out there i began to become aware not only firstly about

00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:49.040
[Guest]: the awareness of being political that you have to be political you cannot completely cut yourself

00:57:49.040 --> 00:57:56.160
[Guest]: off from everything around you and say that oh i'm apolitical that was the preserve of the

00:57:56.160 --> 00:58:02.080
[Guest]: extremely privileged i understood that very quickly i also understood very quickly that

00:58:03.280 --> 00:58:10.560
[Guest]: when people say things like you know oh those people like i keep slipping back into hindi

00:58:10.560 --> 00:58:16.880
[Guest]: because you know that's the conversation around me but uh people say things like you know amongst

00:58:16.880 --> 00:58:22.080
[Amit Varma]: those people these things happen it's it's actually okay to slip into hindi i think my

00:58:22.080 --> 00:58:28.080
[Guest]: listeners will get it like okay all right something like that yeah something like that

00:58:34.880 --> 00:58:38.480
[Guest]: like you know the poor don't want to study they don't want to get ahead in life

00:58:38.480 --> 00:58:43.920
[Guest]: and those are the kind of things which you absorb without you don't really question that very much

00:58:43.920 --> 00:58:50.160
[Guest]: and then when i went when i actually went out there and i saw how hard people work to just get

00:58:50.160 --> 00:58:55.360
[Guest]: a chance at education there are women holding down three or four or eight different jobs

00:58:55.360 --> 00:59:01.280
[Guest]: to be able to put their kids through school and and they trust that that will somehow lift them

00:59:01.280 --> 00:59:05.840
[Guest]: out of poverty save them from the worst things that they're out there there were a lot of things

00:59:05.840 --> 00:59:13.280
[Guest]: a lot of things out there i remember when i was one of my assignments i was sent off to

00:59:13.280 --> 00:59:18.880
[Guest]: cover a raid on a brother in i was working in midday at the time and it was just one of those

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:24.560
[Guest]: things where i mean one i didn't even tell my family that i'm going to do it because i mean

00:59:24.560 --> 00:59:31.040
[Guest]: what do you tell them i think i would have been sucked into the kind of confrontation i could not

00:59:31.040 --> 00:59:37.520
[Guest]: afford to have at the time but even from my own point of view i of course it it was extremely

00:59:37.520 --> 00:59:42.960
[Guest]: frightening extremely frightening just the idea of even when you're going with the police it's

00:59:42.960 --> 00:59:51.120
[Guest]: accompanying a police team i wasn't going on my own but the idea of being a woman going into a

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:56.480
[Guest]: space which i understood instinctively to be hostile to women i mean these were sex workers

00:59:56.480 --> 01:00:02.880
[Guest]: yes and some of them may be voluntary sex workers but i understood it to be intrinsically hostile

01:00:02.880 --> 01:00:12.240
[Guest]: to the women and i was very frightened and uh i remember thinking that this was a

01:00:13.680 --> 01:00:19.120
[Guest]: quote-unquote not nice thing i'm doing you know like nice girls even for their work they don't

01:00:19.120 --> 01:00:23.280
[Guest]: go to brothers like what is this what am i doing here in the middle of the night with these cops

01:00:23.280 --> 01:00:30.320
[Guest]: and who hangs out with cops anyway you know um and i remember having all these questions in my

01:00:30.320 --> 01:00:36.320
[Guest]: mind but i'd actually never seen an actual sex worker in my life before and this is true of i

01:00:36.320 --> 01:00:43.600
[Guest]: think women in particular men might notice or men might even you know enter into a conversation with

01:00:43.600 --> 01:00:49.360
[Guest]: the sex worker because that is the nature of the transaction but for women particularly

01:00:49.360 --> 01:00:55.840
[Guest]: quote-unquote nice you know or respectable whatever that means the idea of respectability

01:00:56.400 --> 01:01:02.080
[Guest]: was something i had not challenged as a 2021 just took it for granted that yeah i'm respectable and

01:01:02.080 --> 01:01:08.800
[Guest]: you have to hold on to this idea of your respectability but i did know quite certainly

01:01:08.800 --> 01:01:14.320
[Guest]: that respectability is constantly under attack that even if you are somebody from a quote-unquote

01:01:14.320 --> 01:01:19.600
[Guest]: respectable family your respectability is constantly under attack it is constantly being

01:01:19.600 --> 01:01:27.200
[Guest]: threatened premarital sex can threaten it photos of you uh you know nude photos of you can threaten

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:32.160
[Guest]: it anybody makes a random comment about you that can threaten it somebody goes to your parents and

01:01:32.160 --> 01:01:37.680
[Guest]: says oh we saw this girl sitting so and so at that time and with a boy and then that threatens it

01:01:37.680 --> 01:01:43.680
[Guest]: if you're seen smoking then that threatens your idea of whether or not you're respectable all

01:01:43.680 --> 01:01:49.760
[Guest]: these things i knew and i knew that you have to at all times guard against any the smallest assault

01:01:49.760 --> 01:01:55.120
[Guest]: upon your respectability because then your life could be ruined etc etc and then here i was then

01:01:55.120 --> 01:02:02.400
[Guest]: doing this thing attending a raid uh where you were looking for underage girls and that one night

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:11.760
[Guest]: and that one night i have to say that so much just fell away uh first my ideas about because

01:02:11.760 --> 01:02:18.320
[Guest]: these were just things i'd seen in movies you know never never actually met someone but then i go in

01:02:18.320 --> 01:02:22.320
[Guest]: and i see that there are all these girls they're dressed up and they're being picked out by somebody

01:02:22.320 --> 01:02:27.840
[Guest]: who's pretending to be a client but is actually a cop and then i saw the cops beating up some of

01:02:27.840 --> 01:02:35.520
[Guest]: the men who were possibly workers pimps or whoever they were procurers and then i sat down with some

01:02:35.520 --> 01:02:41.280
[Guest]: of those girls while the raid was underway because what else could i do i had nowhere else to go my

01:02:41.280 --> 01:02:47.200
[Guest]: job was just to sit and watch what was happening um i'm sitting with those girls and i was clearly

01:02:47.200 --> 01:02:53.040
[Guest]: upset i i don't think i was like bawling or anything but i was upset enough that even the

01:02:53.040 --> 01:02:58.960
[Guest]: cops noticed and they turned around and somebody said that you know somebody take this girl away

01:02:58.960 --> 01:03:04.640
[Guest]: because she's going to start crying any minute now and then some of these girls the sex workers

01:03:04.640 --> 01:03:09.840
[Guest]: took me away they took me to another room and they allowed the raid to progress as it was progressing

01:03:10.720 --> 01:03:15.680
[Guest]: and they thought for some reason i don't know why maybe they picked up on my fear or whatever it was

01:03:15.680 --> 01:03:22.400
[Guest]: they sat me down they held my hands and they said didi koi baat nahi and it was just so ridiculous

01:03:22.400 --> 01:03:26.400
[Guest]: because they were the ones who were suffering the raid the cops were going to i mean nothing was

01:03:26.400 --> 01:03:34.320
[Guest]: going to happen to me i was going to go back home at the end of that night um and even as a 21 22

01:03:34.320 --> 01:03:40.720
[Guest]: maybe a year old i was aware of this irony that this is absolutely stupid why are these girls

01:03:40.720 --> 01:03:46.400
[Guest]: holding my hand and telling me ki didi you know uh you don't worry i mean i should be the one

01:03:46.400 --> 01:03:52.320
[Guest]: telling them that didi you don't worry they're younger to me they were 17 years old 18 years old

01:03:52.320 --> 01:03:57.840
[Guest]: many of them were minors they ended up doing the tests and finding that these 16 15 year old girls

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:05.440
[Guest]: i think a lot of my biases crumpled immediately in that moment every bias i had held about

01:04:06.160 --> 01:04:11.040
[Guest]: what kind of woman deserves to be treated in what way that in that one night that collapsed

01:04:11.040 --> 01:04:19.200
[Guest]: completely i also remember thinking that about the nature of policing for the first time because it

01:04:19.200 --> 01:04:25.120
[Guest]: was first time i had seen anyone hit a grown man you know when you come from families where

01:04:25.840 --> 01:04:30.560
[Guest]: you don't i mean i had seen violence like in school i had seen violence kids getting beaten

01:04:30.560 --> 01:04:37.440
[Guest]: up i'd never seen a grown man be beaten up i saw that that randomly cops just seeing a man and one

01:04:37.440 --> 01:04:44.240
[Guest]: top and he could be a client or he could be a one of the people who procures women whoever he was i

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:51.520
[Guest]: don't know it was a very big shock but i also remember thinking that the cops aren't supposed

01:04:51.520 --> 01:04:55.600
[Guest]: to do this this is not how policing is supposed to work you know maybe they've done something

01:04:55.600 --> 01:05:02.400
[Guest]: wrong arrest them take down their statements etc etc i think my ideas about how the police functions

01:05:02.400 --> 01:05:10.000
[Guest]: also changed that day i began to understand that that that things don't happen the way

01:05:10.560 --> 01:05:14.960
[Guest]: they're supposed to and that the things i've seen and read in movies and read in books

01:05:15.520 --> 01:05:22.720
[Guest]: are not the way real life is was introduced to real life so to speak and i was also introduced

01:05:22.720 --> 01:05:27.760
[Guest]: to and once you start questioning the things you've inherited the respectability bias that

01:05:27.760 --> 01:05:33.280
[Guest]: you've inherited then you start questioning everything else i think for me that was like that

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:38.640
[Amit Varma]: that one night i will never forget and i've actually uh you know there's a talk on youtube

01:05:38.640 --> 01:05:42.880
[Amit Varma]: where you also spoke about that one night and it's very cinematic actually that image of you

01:05:42.880 --> 01:05:47.840
[Amit Varma]: sitting on a bed being consoled by the girls your theme the context in which you brought this up

01:05:47.840 --> 01:05:52.960
[Amit Varma]: was again something that i'd like you to elaborate on because it's very interesting to me about a

01:05:52.960 --> 01:05:58.080
[Amit Varma]: journey that journalists should take but some may not which is discovering the difference between

01:05:58.080 --> 01:06:02.080
[Amit Varma]: facts and the truth that when you are a journalist you're reporting you're going out you're getting

01:06:02.080 --> 01:06:06.640
[Amit Varma]: facts you're taking quotes this happened so and so said this so and so said that but there's a

01:06:06.640 --> 01:06:11.840
[Amit Varma]: layer behind it that is a truth and i presume you mentioned this story because you know uh some of

01:06:11.840 --> 01:06:16.880
[Amit Varma]: the facts fall away and some of the truth comes out and uh you you see those layers now i would

01:06:16.880 --> 01:06:21.840
[Amit Varma]: imagine that then like once this happens a switch has gone off it's never going back again you're

01:06:21.840 --> 01:06:26.800
[Amit Varma]: never only going to look at facts again you're going to look for truth and your notion of what

01:06:26.800 --> 01:06:31.840
[Amit Varma]: the truth is will then evolve with time and what the kind of stories that you do the kind of work

01:06:31.840 --> 01:06:38.160
[Amit Varma]: that you do will be predicated on that uh on uh you know that evolving kind of frame of the world

01:06:38.160 --> 01:06:44.000
[Amit Varma]: so tell me a bit about one the different directions of your thought as all of this happens and two how

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:48.800
[Amit Varma]: you start thinking about the kind of work that you want to do because very soon you go beyond

01:06:48.800 --> 01:06:53.920
[Amit Varma]: journalism you of course were one of the early bloggers uh like me back in the day uh is that

01:06:53.920 --> 01:06:58.080
[Amit Varma]: something that freed you in different ways and helped you explore subjects you would otherwise

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:04.560
[Amit Varma]: not be able to write about and then on to fiction drama all of that what was that kind of journey

01:07:04.560 --> 01:07:11.360
[Amit Varma]: like and that distinction between facts and truth how how hard it is to even define uh what truth is

01:07:11.360 --> 01:07:16.960
[Amit Varma]: because i think what most of us do is the world is too complex to figure out every aspect of it

01:07:16.960 --> 01:07:21.280
[Amit Varma]: right so you adopt a lens and you look at it and it could be a gray lens and bombay looks gray

01:07:21.280 --> 01:07:25.600
[Amit Varma]: and suddenly you take away the filter that hides the red and how you see the red also

01:07:25.600 --> 01:07:30.160
[Amit Varma]: so what is that process like do you keep examining your biases and your lenses and your frames

01:07:30.800 --> 01:07:36.000
[Guest]: i kind of do and i think my early journalistic training had a lot to do with it i think i got

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:41.200
[Guest]: really lucky especially that one and a half year that i spent at midday i think i just gave the

01:07:41.200 --> 01:07:45.440
[Guest]: example of the raid but i did a bunch of things like that my editor at the time was akar patel

01:07:45.440 --> 01:07:50.000
[Guest]: and there's a big one for just go out there and check what's happening just see what happened

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:57.280
[Guest]: like that so for example i'll give you another example um this was one of the major stories i

01:07:57.280 --> 01:08:02.800
[Guest]: did where somebody wanted something done about the rights of the disabled right people who are

01:08:02.800 --> 01:08:07.280
[Guest]: differently abled or disabled in the city now how do you write about that one way of saying is

01:08:07.280 --> 01:08:14.080
[Guest]: just to say that okay you know the city doesn't do enough and leave it at that but he said okay

01:08:14.080 --> 01:08:18.560
[Guest]: go put yourself in a wheelchair and figure out what it's like so i spent the day traveling

01:08:18.560 --> 01:08:22.560
[Guest]: around the city as a disabled person so one of the first things that happens is obviously

01:08:22.560 --> 01:08:27.600
[Guest]: my own filters come crashing down right because i had never thought about what it's like for

01:08:27.600 --> 01:08:32.480
[Guest]: people who are in a wheelchair what is the city like because you are abled you just take it for

01:08:32.480 --> 01:08:38.880
[Guest]: granted that the city is fine right what's wrong with the set of staircases i mean um and even if

01:08:38.880 --> 01:08:43.280
[Guest]: you do know that okay so people in wheelchairs can't go here so then you say well if they can't

01:08:43.280 --> 01:08:49.280
[Guest]: they can't and you shrug it off and you don't think more once i did that i started to see so

01:08:49.280 --> 01:08:54.560
[Guest]: many things in so many different ways not just that you can't climb a flight of stairs so okay

01:08:54.560 --> 01:08:58.640
[Guest]: maybe you can't get from platform number one to platform number five maybe it's difficult

01:08:59.360 --> 01:09:03.120
[Guest]: then you find that even if you get to platform number five the gap between the train and the

01:09:03.120 --> 01:09:08.000
[Guest]: platform is too big and you can't actually you know the train doesn't stop long enough for you

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:11.280
[Guest]: to get off the wheelchair fold up the wheelchair put the wheelchair on even if you have people

01:09:11.280 --> 01:09:16.000
[Guest]: helping you that won't happen then you see you can't enter cinemas then you see you can't enter

01:09:16.560 --> 01:09:21.440
[Guest]: eating spaces then you see that something else even if you need to go to a doctor in a taxi

01:09:21.440 --> 01:09:26.000
[Guest]: the taxis aren't big enough mostly to hold a wheelchair so i had the photographer with me

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:31.440
[Guest]: who was playing along pretending that i was actually in a wheelchair and he was having to

01:09:31.440 --> 01:09:37.040
[Guest]: pick me up and carry me and put me in the cab and then fold my wheelchair and the taxi driver

01:09:37.040 --> 01:09:41.200
[Guest]: was very concerned because that once you fold up the wheelchair it doesn't fit into the back of the

01:09:41.200 --> 01:09:50.000
[Guest]: taxi all the different ways in which the city is not meant it is not designed for people who are

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:56.400
[Guest]: different from the norm and then also to become aware that that person could be me i am able today

01:09:56.400 --> 01:10:01.360
[Guest]: but i could be disabled tomorrow something could happen it could be temporary or it could be

01:10:01.360 --> 01:10:08.000
[Guest]: permanent i could grow old the city is not designed for the elderly and most cities aren't

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:14.160
[Guest]: so in all these different ways i think i was constantly being pushed right to see that okay

01:10:14.160 --> 01:10:18.400
[Guest]: how long does this happen when you call the police station how long how many rings before somebody

01:10:18.400 --> 01:10:23.040
[Guest]: picks up these were all the different ways in which i was being exposed i think for me also

01:10:23.040 --> 01:10:29.200
[Guest]: it was a lot of exposure intense exposure of somebody who had been so under exposed like

01:10:29.200 --> 01:10:36.080
[Guest]: within two years this much exposure was a bit much also and i think that those two or three

01:10:37.280 --> 01:10:44.160
[Guest]: four years of early journalism really did shape and unshape me quite a bit after that i think but

01:10:44.160 --> 01:10:49.440
[Guest]: however this creative urge was there within me i think even when i quit my first reporting job

01:10:50.480 --> 01:10:55.840
[Guest]: i quit it thinking that this is too intense i want to sit at home and write poetry and of course

01:10:55.840 --> 01:11:01.920
[Guest]: within a month i learned my lesson because writing poetry does not pay the bills and i had to go back

01:11:01.920 --> 01:11:07.760
[Guest]: of course and find a job but this creative urge also was there and that one month when i did

01:11:07.760 --> 01:11:13.040
[Guest]: sit home and write poetry all the new things i had learned the things that i did not have time for

01:11:13.040 --> 01:11:18.240
[Guest]: the course of a regular reporting life the ways in which my poetry was changing the ways in which

01:11:18.240 --> 01:11:24.560
[Guest]: i was changing and learning to see the world in a different way um that i had time to process

01:11:24.560 --> 01:11:29.760
[Guest]: and sit down and maybe write a couple of new poems and then go back and then write in different ways

01:11:31.200 --> 01:11:35.600
[Guest]: so i was always doing that i think and and i kept quitting and kept going back because i

01:11:35.600 --> 01:11:42.560
[Guest]: didn't have much of an option but i think by the time i was around 24-25 it was clear to me that i

01:11:42.560 --> 01:11:48.000
[Guest]: also want more that i don't want just journalism i want to do more i want to tell other stories

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:54.240
[Guest]: stories that i cannot tell as journalists by the time i started blogging it was around i think end

01:11:54.240 --> 01:12:01.680
[Guest]: of 2004-2005 i knew journalism enough to know that most things that i'm thinking and feeling

01:12:01.680 --> 01:12:06.080
[Guest]: are not going to make it into the copy even if you're writing for a magazine and so you've got

01:12:06.080 --> 01:12:12.640
[Guest]: more words you don't have to stop at 300 words you can write say 2000 words but you're still not

01:12:12.640 --> 01:12:20.240
[Guest]: going to be able to write the truth as i experience it and see it and the many layers of truth so for

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:26.720
[Guest]: example something as simple as i'll give you an example of what delhi feels like after it's rained

01:12:27.920 --> 01:12:32.400
[Guest]: in the morning right um i was in delhi i'd moved to delhi by that time

01:12:34.400 --> 01:12:40.560
[Guest]: now if i'm a reporter say a normal you know regular city reporter i can just say unseasonal

01:12:40.560 --> 01:12:47.520
[Guest]: rain at delhi and so and so time whatever whatever and or traffic stopped or you know if traffic

01:12:47.520 --> 01:12:53.200
[Guest]: doesn't stop and if it's not unseasonal then why will you write about it raining right it rained

01:12:53.200 --> 01:12:58.640
[Guest]: so that's two words what does that convey to the reader does it convey anything of beauty

01:12:58.640 --> 01:13:04.640
[Guest]: does it convey um that particular way in which you're learning to see the city it's the air is

01:13:04.640 --> 01:13:10.640
[Guest]: just a little crisper a little cleaner and there's dew everywhere or all surfaces are wet and the

01:13:10.640 --> 01:13:15.200
[Guest]: quality and texture i became interested in capturing that too because that is also a

01:13:15.200 --> 01:13:19.920
[Guest]: different kind of truth a different kind of experience reality and i found that blogging

01:13:19.920 --> 01:13:24.320
[Guest]: gave me that freedom there's nowhere else i could do it even for free there was no other space out

01:13:24.320 --> 01:13:29.840
[Guest]: there there were no other lit journals that would just publish me talking about how i'm thinking

01:13:29.840 --> 01:13:36.320
[Guest]: or feeling about a certain morning a certain moment in time and blogging allowed me to do that

01:13:36.320 --> 01:13:42.320
[Guest]: it also allowed me to talk about the story behind the story so i write the story for the magazine

01:13:42.320 --> 01:13:47.680
[Guest]: but also then i get to write about what the train journey was like that i couldn't get

01:13:47.680 --> 01:13:54.720
[Guest]: reservation and this is what it felt like or or the kind of conversations you overhear in budget

01:13:54.720 --> 01:14:01.200
[Guest]: hotels and i found that interesting i wanted to capture that too and so i think blogging then

01:14:01.200 --> 01:14:07.120
[Guest]: became the next way i started to be formed as a writer as a writer of prose particularly that

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:12.560
[Guest]: it was crucial to me learning how to put experience and words together and capture

01:14:13.120 --> 01:14:16.960
[Guest]: different kinds of truths and and try and make sense of the world around me

01:14:19.120 --> 01:14:25.440
[Guest]: and then rama i think came after one more leap i had done some more journalism particularly in

01:14:25.440 --> 01:14:32.080
[Guest]: rural areas for i think three three and a half years and i had just started to write my first

