01:41:33.680 --> 01:41:39.760
[Guest]: think about it uh in the context of colonization particularly because once i got into the history

01:41:39.760 --> 01:41:45.840
[Guest]: of it uh of you know what is this place i got interested in that you know how how do people

01:41:45.840 --> 01:41:50.880
[Guest]: just land up in the middle of nowhere and create something new and more importantly what was that

01:41:50.880 --> 01:41:56.080
[Guest]: before in india at least i don't think there there is any place where there is nothing before

01:41:57.200 --> 01:42:02.880
[Guest]: and and in colonial narratives and colonization narratives or rather

01:42:02.880 --> 01:42:08.480
[Guest]: counter-colonial narratives we see a lot of this of you know there was nothing there before

01:42:09.760 --> 01:42:18.160
[Guest]: and uh for example in the australian context i've read this book i think it is called the

01:42:18.160 --> 01:42:21.760
[Guest]: the dark river or the secret river or something like that which is about

01:42:23.440 --> 01:42:31.200
[Guest]: people mostly convicts who were sent away from england to australia and uh it's a lovely book

01:42:31.200 --> 01:42:38.000
[Guest]: it's a lovely book it it also takes a not unsympathetic view of the the people who went

01:42:38.000 --> 01:42:42.400
[Guest]: because their lives were very difficult too and and the laws were terrible in england at the time

01:42:42.400 --> 01:42:48.000
[Guest]: you could be uh jailed for like kids were being jailed for stealing bread and things like that

01:42:48.000 --> 01:42:52.080
[Guest]: and a lot of people who were sent away to australia as convicts were just teenagers

01:42:52.080 --> 01:42:59.360
[Guest]: who'd stolen a hanky or a pot or a chicken or things like that just food so these were

01:42:59.360 --> 01:43:04.480
[Guest]: desperately poor people and it was a miracle they survived that long journey going to a completely

01:43:04.480 --> 01:43:11.200
[Guest]: alien place with nothing really and and if you survive then okay maybe you could make a new life

01:43:11.200 --> 01:43:19.680
[Guest]: there but they show up there and the thing is the point of that book really is that there was

01:43:19.680 --> 01:43:24.160
[Guest]: somebody there and that they knew there was somebody there they pretended that there was

01:43:24.160 --> 01:43:29.040
[Guest]: nothing there they pretended that these people were savages and that they didn't know agriculture

01:43:29.040 --> 01:43:34.320
[Guest]: and that we went there and we made agriculture but then the writer says that through the this

01:43:34.320 --> 01:43:45.120
[Guest]: family that has gone there and the protagonist the man of the family he sees that there are patches

01:43:45.120 --> 01:43:50.000
[Guest]: which were already being cultivated it wasn't the same kind of cultivation that the english were

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:55.440
[Guest]: used to but it was cultivation they had agriculture they knew how to make fire they knew how to hunt

01:43:55.440 --> 01:44:03.280
[Guest]: kangaroo they had their own lives their own whatever it was and when they began to take

01:44:03.280 --> 01:44:08.080
[Guest]: over the lands there was a lot of land but when they began to take over these lands they were

01:44:08.080 --> 01:44:13.600
[Guest]: aware the new settlers that they were taking something over it wasn't uninhabited land

01:44:15.440 --> 01:44:20.640
[Guest]: and you see this within india quite a bit you know when something new comes up it doesn't come

01:44:20.640 --> 01:44:26.720
[Guest]: out of nothing that there is something there and what happens to that something then is the big

01:44:26.720 --> 01:44:32.720
[Guest]: question it's not as simple as imperialism for example because we are a union right what is the

01:44:32.720 --> 01:44:41.040
[Guest]: meaning of india it is the union of india so people are free to live and work and capitalize on the

01:44:41.040 --> 01:44:46.800
[Guest]: natural resources of the land anywhere in the country that that is part of being what a union

01:44:46.800 --> 01:44:55.200
[Guest]: means at the same time there is a kind of taking over a kind of effacement of what was there before

01:44:55.200 --> 01:45:02.160
[Guest]: in my case it was very stark because the name of where we lived it was written up there in painted

01:45:02.160 --> 01:45:09.200
[Guest]: in limestone on the hills right so in a way it was like you were stamping the landscape itself

01:45:09.200 --> 01:45:17.520
[Guest]: with the name of an industrial township right and that the name of the industrial township is what

01:45:17.520 --> 01:45:24.320
[Guest]: the township does not take the name of the places that existed there before it takes its name from

01:45:24.320 --> 01:45:30.160
[Guest]: the names of industrialists so it's effectively the name what is jk the name the initials of the

01:45:30.960 --> 01:45:35.920
[Guest]: industrialists the family that owned the place and this is true of others also i shouldn't single

01:45:35.920 --> 01:45:41.760
[Guest]: out one place it's true of tata nagar for example it's true of other places elsewhere you know

01:45:41.760 --> 01:45:48.640
[Guest]: wherever these sort of colonies come up the assumption is like for example tata nagar what

01:45:48.640 --> 01:45:55.920
[Guest]: what was there there was something there right wasn't that nothing existed but when an enterprise

01:45:55.920 --> 01:46:02.720
[Guest]: a privately owned enterprise enters a space transforms it manufactures something there

01:46:02.720 --> 01:46:09.280
[Guest]: creates new buildings etc but effaces what was there before starting with the name you know

01:46:09.280 --> 01:46:15.440
[Guest]: starting with stamping your own name on the landscape to then other things then using the

01:46:15.440 --> 01:46:21.760
[Guest]: natural resources obviously the land is of course used the mountains are used the limestone is used

01:46:21.760 --> 01:46:30.560
[Guest]: water is used groundwater or the river water is used and all of this goes into doing something

01:46:30.560 --> 01:46:34.800
[Guest]: manufacturing cement right now you can argue that it's for the good of the country because we need

01:46:34.800 --> 01:46:41.920
[Guest]: cement for construction and so on but where profit is concerned the profit does not stay here the

01:46:41.920 --> 01:46:48.800
[Guest]: profit is channeled out somewhere in these respects i do think it is similar to the process of

01:46:48.800 --> 01:46:54.560
[Guest]: colonization because when you construct a colony come in there sometimes you change names sometimes

01:46:54.560 --> 01:47:02.800
[Guest]: you don't you promise the local population something i mean even in imperial terms that

01:47:02.800 --> 01:47:07.280
[Guest]: this was what was done it was not that the locals had nothing to do with the enterprise of course

01:47:07.280 --> 01:47:13.680
[Guest]: they did the armies were indian by and large everything was indian but the key thing was that

01:47:13.680 --> 01:47:19.440
[Guest]: the prophets left the place so in our case in a large sense when we speak of colonization we speak

01:47:19.440 --> 01:47:25.920
[Guest]: of nations or continents you know like whatever south asia was we were completely colonized and

01:47:25.920 --> 01:47:30.560
[Guest]: we had nothing at the end of all of these things railways were built but not to our purposes

01:47:31.200 --> 01:47:34.880
[Guest]: things were being made not things that we needed things some other people needed

01:47:35.440 --> 01:47:42.160
[Guest]: and they decided for us how much we would participate and they took back the profits

01:47:42.160 --> 01:47:48.160
[Guest]: of that enterprise to another location so in this way i think when someone enters a place

01:47:48.160 --> 01:47:52.800
[Guest]: yes they try to do their bit they try to give back to the community they set up schools hospitals all

01:47:52.800 --> 01:47:59.120
[Guest]: of that no disputing that but what is the primary purpose here the primary purpose is that you will

01:47:59.120 --> 01:48:05.120
[Guest]: enter a space use the natural resources take the help of the local people create something

01:48:05.120 --> 01:48:11.600
[Guest]: so that you may profit and that place is not the primary holder of that profit and you yourself do

01:48:11.600 --> 01:48:17.920
[Guest]: not live there you think of something else's home right you set up industry somewhere else you have

01:48:17.920 --> 01:48:22.960
[Guest]: your life somewhere else you're invested in making that place ultimately more habitable

01:48:22.960 --> 01:48:28.080
[Guest]: than this place which you know will ultimately run out of deposits how long can a natural resource

01:48:28.080 --> 01:48:34.880
[Guest]: last it's going to come to an end maybe in maybe not in 10 years maybe after 50 years what after

01:48:34.880 --> 01:48:40.560
[Guest]: that the money isn't staying in that community so those were some of the things i was thinking

01:48:40.560 --> 01:48:45.520
[Guest]: and these are very complex questions because it brings you back to the question of so then

01:48:45.520 --> 01:48:51.920
[Guest]: should we have no development so who can exploit what and in what way but i think it's worth having

01:48:51.920 --> 01:48:58.400
[Guest]: a conversation about how much of the profit and how much of the resources can be taken

01:48:58.400 --> 01:49:05.840
[Guest]: and how far they can be taken from the place where they are being exploited that's illuminating i'll

