[Amit Varma]: them into your narrative and uh you know as if uh and subsuming them now now my question here is uh

01:52:38.160 --> 01:52:42.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of what i wondered about is this i i'd done an episode on the right to property with shruti

01:52:42.560 --> 01:52:48.320
[Amit Varma]: rajgopalan ages ago i think it was episode 26 where we kind of both felt strongly that the

01:52:48.320 --> 01:52:52.880
[Amit Varma]: right to property which which was diluted massively should have remained a right and

01:52:52.880 --> 01:52:58.640
[Amit Varma]: a lot of the sort of solutions to this kind of situation lies in the proper application of that

01:52:58.640 --> 01:53:03.520
[Amit Varma]: because what should obviously happen in these cases is if the adivasis have occupied the land

01:53:03.520 --> 01:53:08.480
[Amit Varma]: for centuries they should own the land and then they do with it what they do now there are two

01:53:08.480 --> 01:53:13.200
[Amit Varma]: things that can happen one is that they don't own the land and therefore the state will get together

01:53:13.200 --> 01:53:17.920
[Amit Varma]: with cronies and they'll do all of this nonsense like another scam that is often run is you can't

01:53:17.920 --> 01:53:22.480
[Amit Varma]: sell agricultural land for non-agricultural purposes right so agricultural land therefore

01:53:23.280 --> 01:53:27.600
[Amit Varma]: to the farmer has no value because he can't sell it to anyone but if you change the land use

01:53:27.600 --> 01:53:32.080
[Amit Varma]: certificate it can be worth 40 times as much so what the state will often do is they'll do land

01:53:32.080 --> 01:53:37.360
[Amit Varma]: acquisition they'll say pay the farmer one rupee and then they'll change the land use certificate

01:53:37.360 --> 01:53:41.280
[Amit Varma]: and you know give it to the industrialist or the industrialist changes the land use certificate

01:53:41.280 --> 01:53:46.480
[Amit Varma]: allegedly what happened in the Robert Wadra case the other aspect which is where I am kind of

01:53:47.200 --> 01:53:53.200
[Amit Varma]: where I don't know what to think is that let's say the adivasis are given ownership of the land

01:53:53.200 --> 01:53:58.080
[Amit Varma]: but then these private parties go to them and they buy it off anyway individually one by one

01:53:58.080 --> 01:54:02.240
[Amit Varma]: promising this promising that giving so much money and they may not even you know they may

01:54:02.240 --> 01:54:06.880
[Amit Varma]: be asymmetric information they may not even have the all the information to make a good judgment

01:54:06.880 --> 01:54:13.200
[Amit Varma]: and it goes away is that part of the mix of what happened that the the original people in that land

01:54:13.200 --> 01:54:18.160
[Amit Varma]: did own some of the land and sell it off without knowing and if that is to be the case what would

01:54:18.160 --> 01:54:23.600
[Amit Varma]: be a solution there because I think the other solution that I often hear from activists that

01:54:23.600 --> 01:54:28.720
[Amit Varma]: you have collective ownership by the tribe of a particular piece of land just doesn't seem to

01:54:28.720 --> 01:54:33.440
[Amit Varma]: work for me because it ignores individual autonomy and I think it's making the same mistake of

01:54:33.440 --> 01:54:37.760
[Amit Varma]: thinking in terms of a collective so you know you've been to all of these places and reported

01:54:37.760 --> 01:54:41.920
[Amit Varma]: from that and your book really didn't have these sort of details obviously because you were looking

01:54:41.920 --> 01:54:46.080
[Amit Varma]: more into the sociological and cultural aspects which we'll come back to but what are your

01:54:46.080 --> 01:54:52.560
[Guest]: thoughts on this so one of the things Amit that is really difficult for me I don't have a clear

01:54:52.560 --> 01:55:01.360
[Guest]: position on this but I think one of the things I struggle with is the question of our notions about

01:55:01.360 --> 01:55:08.560
[Guest]: what is ownership now a lot of indigenous tribes including certain adivasi tribes not all

01:55:08.560 --> 01:55:13.920
[Guest]: adivasis in this particular place that I wrote about for example they did have very clear notions

01:55:13.920 --> 01:55:20.880
[Guest]: of private ownership and and there were families who owned xyz and and those families did whatever

01:55:20.880 --> 01:55:25.040
[Guest]: money they were given and I think that if there had been much more money given they would do the

01:55:25.040 --> 01:55:31.520
[Guest]: same thing again so I don't think that that in in this particular case that this was a problem

01:55:31.520 --> 01:55:36.480
[Guest]: but there are tribes that do not believe in private ownership they do believe that the earth

01:55:36.480 --> 01:55:42.880
[Guest]: is holy or that you know nature is does not belong to individuals and that it should not belong to

01:55:42.880 --> 01:55:51.520
[Guest]: individuals and I see that point of view too I personally it is true that if I owned property

01:55:51.520 --> 01:55:55.920
[Guest]: I would like to think of that as my property and not think of it as other people's property that

01:55:55.920 --> 01:56:04.320
[Guest]: it is true speaking for myself but I also get the the logic behind people saying and I also see the

01:56:04.320 --> 01:56:10.480
[Guest]: limits of private ownership so when it comes to water for example I have forgotten the name of

01:56:10.480 --> 01:56:18.160
[Guest]: the guy but some very rich person in the west on whoever he was said something ridiculous that

01:56:18.160 --> 01:56:22.960
[Guest]: there's no need for water to be a basic human right and that it should be privatized

01:56:24.720 --> 01:56:29.920
[Guest]: if you keep pushing natural resources and land is ultimately a natural resource you have to

01:56:30.640 --> 01:56:38.000
[Guest]: understand that property is is at the heart of it it is nature and within that comes everything

01:56:38.000 --> 01:56:44.960
[Guest]: else so minerals under the soil whatever you can mine etc etc but land air and water

01:56:44.960 --> 01:56:52.160
[Guest]: are also inalienable rights right and there are limits to the transferability of that if

01:56:52.160 --> 01:56:57.840
[Guest]: what is next air then and we are coming quite close to the point where we might end up bottling

01:56:57.840 --> 01:57:05.040
[Guest]: and buying air and deciding that that you know what part of the planet is habitable and what

01:57:05.040 --> 01:57:11.200
[Guest]: isn't and then what do you do and I think we've actually already painted ourselves as a species

01:57:11.200 --> 01:57:16.160
[Guest]: painted ourselves into this corner if we're dangerously close to having to take these awful

01:57:16.160 --> 01:57:22.560
[Guest]: decisions but where indigenous tribes are concerned I think from the land and water perspective they

01:57:22.560 --> 01:57:30.240
[Guest]: got there much faster they're not there yet as far as air is concerned but if you say that land

01:57:30.240 --> 01:57:37.120
[Guest]: ownership itself is sacrosanct then I think that there are limits that to that idea that there that

01:57:37.120 --> 01:57:43.760
[Guest]: there that if you make a purchase obviously in law that purchase will hold right

01:57:45.920 --> 01:57:52.400
[Guest]: but if you make a purchase and you destroy the land and you can legally because you own it

01:57:53.120 --> 01:57:59.520
[Guest]: the impact of that decision is felt by other people who own other land but not yours

01:58:00.080 --> 01:58:06.240
[Guest]: if you poison the groundwater it doesn't just affect your piece of land it affects everyone

01:58:06.240 --> 01:58:12.400
[Guest]: so which is one of the big problems with this industrial takeover and like Gurgaon for example

01:58:12.400 --> 01:58:16.560
[Guest]: one of the big flooding problem who could have imagined Gurgaon is a dry place it's flooding now

01:58:16.560 --> 01:58:23.120
[Guest]: who could have imagined that that would happen but it's happening because bad construction taking too

01:58:23.120 --> 01:58:29.760
[Guest]: much groundwater blocking off river access etc it's happening in all cities now so the impact

01:58:29.760 --> 01:58:36.720
[Guest]: of one decision on private property done legally done the right way even then I feel that one has

01:58:36.720 --> 01:58:42.960
[Guest]: to kind of understand that because we live together the collective idea whether we like it or not we

01:58:42.960 --> 01:58:48.640
[Guest]: are collectively here on the planet so the collective idea must be taken into account

01:58:48.640 --> 01:58:56.240
[Amit Varma]: even as we discuss private property. Yeah my sort of response to that is that I wouldn't say that

01:58:56.240 --> 01:59:00.320
[Amit Varma]: private property is sacrosanct I would say it's necessary and it's necessary because there is

01:59:00.320 --> 01:59:05.440
[Amit Varma]: scarcity and if there is scarcity of something then how does the world work you can't just have

01:59:05.440 --> 01:59:11.200
[Amit Varma]: people fighting all the time over limited resources whereas you know a system of property properly

01:59:11.200 --> 01:59:16.160
[Amit Varma]: administered can work to the you know works much better the other way of looking at it is that I

01:59:16.160 --> 01:59:19.920
[Amit Varma]: think what you point out about what happens if someone poisons groundwater what happens to

01:59:19.920 --> 01:59:23.920
[Amit Varma]: everyone that's much more likely to have happened with collective ownership I mean the tragedy of

01:59:23.920 --> 01:59:29.280
[Amit Varma]: the commons always happens in the commons right you are much more likely to not give a damn about

01:59:29.280 --> 01:59:33.920
[Amit Varma]: the quality of the water or the air or whatever when you don't own a part of it it's you know

01:59:33.920 --> 01:59:37.760
[Amit Varma]: that's kind of where it comes from and without private property I think everything falls apart

01:59:37.760 --> 01:59:42.560
[Amit Varma]: we've seen that all through the 20th century what happened in the Soviet Union and all of that and

01:59:42.560 --> 01:59:47.280
[Amit Varma]: inevitably while it's a very nice concept that we all own everything and we live collectively

01:59:47.280 --> 01:59:52.320
[Amit Varma]: together inevitably you know the powerful will corner everything and the rest of us will be

01:59:52.320 --> 02:00:00.320
[Amit Varma]: vassals and serfs but I you know having said that one is not I think the problem in this case is

02:00:00.320 --> 02:00:05.840
[Amit Varma]: that this is not how property should really be administered I mean if the Adivasis live there

02:00:05.840 --> 02:00:11.200
[Amit Varma]: that's their property then the only question is dealing through you know thinking through

02:00:12.560 --> 02:00:20.160
[Amit Varma]: the naughtier problems that then arise of what if individuals are acting without you know adequate

02:00:20.160 --> 02:00:25.040
[Amit Varma]: information will they make the wrong decisions and even there I would argue that you know as

02:00:25.040 --> 02:00:29.680
[Amit Varma]: as far as individuals are concerned it's sometimes dangerous to sort of condescend to them and say

02:00:29.680 --> 02:00:34.880
[Amit Varma]: that oh they don't know what they are doing so this collective notion of what is right must

02:00:35.840 --> 02:00:42.160
[Amit Varma]: sort of prevail but that said I entirely agree with everything you said about colonization and

02:00:42.160 --> 02:00:48.160
[Amit Varma]: actually go further and not put any caveats there I mean this is what kind of state coercion sort of

02:00:48.160 --> 02:00:54.240
[Guest]: uh leads to so uh so they're abstracted by disagreement please please go ahead if I can

02:00:54.240 --> 02:01:00.880
[Guest]: just add to that um I think one of the problems also with the language of law like we were

02:01:00.880 --> 02:01:05.840
[Guest]: discussing language earlier and the problems with that is that while I agree that things

02:01:05.840 --> 02:01:11.520
[Guest]: should be properly administered etc the question is which brings us to the question of one who's

02:01:11.520 --> 02:01:19.520
[Guest]: doing the administering and secondly how we're defining laws right so um people who can't prove

02:01:19.520 --> 02:01:24.880
[Guest]: that they've lived now now law functions with proof right if and and this doesn't apply just

02:01:24.880 --> 02:01:29.520
[Guest]: to adivasis this apply we're seeing ridiculous cases like people who are alive having to prove

02:01:29.520 --> 02:01:36.160
[Guest]: that they're alive right in and as a legal entity am I even alive if I can't prove am I a citizen if

02:01:36.160 --> 02:01:42.640
[Guest]: I can prove that I'm a citizen this the law is naughty for those reasons too that the burden

02:01:42.640 --> 02:01:49.040
[Guest]: of proof is always on those who who cannot substantiate it and if you don't have paperwork

02:01:49.600 --> 02:01:54.960
[Guest]: let's say we agree that okay there must be other ways apart from paperwork paperwork can be taken

02:01:54.960 --> 02:02:00.640
[Guest]: away from you if there are other ways then what are those other ways those other ways are all

02:02:00.640 --> 02:02:07.920
[Guest]: administration and power structures so somebody the naivete sildar the sarpanch the local guy

02:02:07.920 --> 02:02:13.680
[Guest]: whoever your local clerk is at some local office will then certify or the local cops will certify

02:02:13.680 --> 02:02:17.840
[Guest]: like they do with passports they come to your house and certify that you actually live where

02:02:17.840 --> 02:02:22.240
[Guest]: you claim to live but then that puts you at the mercy of those people right we all know how that

02:02:22.240 --> 02:02:29.120
[Guest]: works uh and then then the law then gets misused so it's a never-ending cycle I think you gave

02:02:29.120 --> 02:02:34.400
[Amit Varma]: I think you gave the example of the Gond tribals that if they interface with you know the state

02:02:34.400 --> 02:02:38.320
[Amit Varma]: the state won't interface with them in their language they won't even recognize their language

02:02:38.320 --> 02:02:42.640
[Amit Varma]: so what are the poor guys going to do quick aside here one of my and this is an outlier but it's an

02:02:42.640 --> 02:02:46.960
[Amit Varma]: interesting example of something like this working out one of my good friends Varun Mitra who's also

02:02:46.960 --> 02:02:52.480
[Amit Varma]: been on this show worked for many years with I think forest tribals in Gujarat to establish land

02:02:52.480 --> 02:02:57.280
[Amit Varma]: ownership and there was a big battle with the state and it took many years and my bad for

02:02:57.280 --> 02:03:01.520
[Amit Varma]: forgetting the other activists at the forefront who worked with him there I've forgotten their

02:03:01.520 --> 02:03:05.920
[Amit Varma]: names but there's a documentary called India Awakes which documents this and I'll link that

02:03:05.920 --> 02:03:10.880
[Amit Varma]: from the show notes and how they managed to establish tribal ownership of the lands they

02:03:10.880 --> 02:03:17.120
[Amit Varma]: claim to own was a use Google Earth data historical Google Earth data going back to all the 15-20 years

02:03:17.120 --> 02:03:21.120
[Amit Varma]: that they needed to show and and they could actually show the houses and the walls and the

02:03:21.120 --> 02:03:26.240
[Amit Varma]: habitations and they won that case the tribals got the land ownership and here's what is so

02:03:26.240 --> 02:03:30.400
[Amit Varma]: remarkable that the moment they got the land ownership guess what is the first thing they did

02:03:30.400 --> 02:03:36.800
[Amit Varma]: they all built toilets you know which is such a sign of incentives that when it's your own home

02:03:36.800 --> 02:03:41.600
[Amit Varma]: then you begin to invest and there is no longer that fear that we could have to leave anytime

02:03:41.600 --> 02:03:48.000
[Amit Varma]: and all of that and I find that an incredibly insightful story of you know technology solving

02:03:48.000 --> 02:03:53.440
[Amit Varma]: almost ancient problem and you know getting people their rights though I fear it might be an outlier

02:03:53.440 --> 02:03:59.600
[Amit Varma]: especially in our dysfunctional state but moving away from sort of the unpleasant topic of the

02:04:00.240 --> 02:04:05.600
[Amit Varma]: state as it were you've also written at various parts in this book about something that has

02:04:05.600 --> 02:04:11.040
[Amit Varma]: a lot of resonance with me which is defining where one is from what is home like you've you

02:04:11.040 --> 02:04:16.000
[Amit Varma]: quoted Maya Angelou in one of your chapters where she says quote the ache for home lives in all of

02:04:16.000 --> 02:04:23.840
[Amit Varma]: us the safe place where we can go as we are and not be questioned and elsewhere when and I found

02:04:23.840 --> 02:04:28.480
[Amit Varma]: this very evocative where you spoke about how you know you wrestled with the tabiz that you were

02:04:28.480 --> 02:04:34.080
[Amit Varma]: wearing with urdu on it and at first you hid it away and then later at one point you decided that

02:04:34.080 --> 02:04:37.920
[Amit Varma]: whenever you wear it you will not hide it you'll wear it openly and at that point you

02:04:38.480 --> 02:04:43.680
[Amit Varma]: wrote quote as much as home is a place of safety it is also a place where you are visible

02:04:43.680 --> 02:04:50.960
[Amit Varma]: stop quote so can you expand a little bit on what your sense of sort of home comes from and where it

02:04:50.960 --> 02:04:56.320
[Amit Varma]: evolves from like you know of course you spent a bunch of your childhood in JK Puram that's not

02:04:56.320 --> 02:05:00.960
[Amit Varma]: so much part of your home you seem to be much closer to Lucknow you've spoken about eastern

02:05:00.960 --> 02:05:06.000
[Amit Varma]: UP, Azamgarh, Allahabad all beautiful chapters in your book which I'll recommend the listeners

02:05:06.000 --> 02:05:11.520
[Amit Varma]: read tell me a bit about the evolving sense of home for you and because it is something I struggle

02:05:11.520 --> 02:05:16.160
[Amit Varma]: with myself in the sense that I've never been anywhere long enough to really call it home if

02:05:16.160 --> 02:05:21.120
[Amit Varma]: anything Bombay is home for me but it is where I live and when I equally think of the related

02:05:21.120 --> 02:05:26.560
[Amit Varma]: subject of what is my community I don't really have one one can build communities of choices

02:05:26.560 --> 02:05:31.520
[Amit Varma]: but otherwise one feels kind of rootless and homeless and all of that and like me you're a

02:05:31.520 --> 02:05:36.960
[Amit Varma]: migrant to this great city or great in terms of big city though it is great in many ways tell me

02:05:36.960 --> 02:05:42.080
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about you know your conceptual sort of journey through understanding what this home

02:05:42.080 --> 02:05:47.840
[Guest]: could mean and what I think when I started out with this book one of the things I had to do was

02:05:47.840 --> 02:05:54.320
[Guest]: you know write an essay and I threw everything I had in my mind into the essay it was kind of just

02:05:54.320 --> 02:05:59.680
[Guest]: sort of free-floating ideas in my head and I start with the image of the grave for example

02:05:59.680 --> 02:06:08.800
[Guest]: and then I move into language and safety notions of safety and alienation and citizenship so I

02:06:08.800 --> 02:06:16.880
[Guest]: think safety is key certainly I think that home needs to be a true home needs to be to feel like

02:06:16.880 --> 02:06:23.120
[Guest]: a safe space and of course lots of homes aren't safe but I think that those homes then are

02:06:23.120 --> 02:06:30.080
[Guest]: possibly either houses rather more than homes or they are homes in the sense that you do love the

02:06:30.080 --> 02:06:35.440
[Guest]: people involved it could be your parents could be your siblings etc but if that space is not safe

02:06:35.440 --> 02:06:40.560
[Guest]: for you ultimately you're not going to feel at home there and you're going to want to leave sooner

02:06:40.560 --> 02:06:45.600
[Guest]: or later that's going to happen and if you're not then you're effectively trapped and a slave and

02:06:45.600 --> 02:06:52.080
[Guest]: it's a horrible situation so safety and freedom are both not only safety but the freedom of

02:06:52.080 --> 02:06:56.720
[Guest]: only safety but the freedom also to grow into the kind of person that you feel like you want to grow

02:06:56.720 --> 02:07:02.560
[Guest]: into as long as you're not obviously hurting other people but I think those two things are

02:07:02.560 --> 02:07:07.760
[Guest]: absolutely key to home and that applies to both your immediate family home and in a larger sense

02:07:07.760 --> 02:07:14.240
[Guest]: to the nation itself that the nation needs to feel like it's a safe place for you and you need

02:07:14.240 --> 02:07:21.680
[Guest]: to be able to when I use the word visible I mean to be seen in the sense that you can be seen to be

02:07:21.680 --> 02:07:27.520
[Guest]: who you are now in my case it could have been I use the example of the Aitul Kursi which I was

02:07:27.520 --> 02:07:34.080
[Guest]: wearing but it could be you know like there was somebody else who was reading an Urdu book on

02:07:34.080 --> 02:07:40.400
[Guest]: the metro train and and was told to go to Pakistan for those reasons or it could be something else

02:07:40.400 --> 02:07:46.800
[Guest]: like it could be a sexuality for example I mean now we have the ongoing argument about same-sex

02:07:46.800 --> 02:07:52.960
[Guest]: marriage it could be that it could be a bunch of things really I mean these things constantly

02:07:52.960 --> 02:08:01.360
[Guest]: evolve like for example when the Khalistan movement was on and there was a lot of killings of Sikhs

02:08:01.360 --> 02:08:05.520
[Guest]: and young Sikh boys particularly a lot of people left the country around that time they sought

02:08:05.520 --> 02:08:10.640
[Guest]: asylum in other countries or they just migrated any way they could and one of the reasons was

02:08:10.640 --> 02:08:15.760
[Guest]: that they were not feeling safe it wasn't just a question of territory it was also that as a

02:08:15.760 --> 02:08:23.680
[Guest]: community that community stopped feeling that the state was doing right by them and they weren't

02:08:23.680 --> 02:08:30.160
[Guest]: sure whether they could trust the state at that particular point of time so I do think that safety

02:08:30.160 --> 02:08:38.080
[Guest]: is key self-expression is key that it could be marital choices or whatever it is that you know

02:08:38.080 --> 02:08:44.640
[Guest]: that it could be language it could be a bunch of other things that I talk about but mainly I think

02:08:44.640 --> 02:08:50.720
[Guest]: it is that a place where you are not being punished for just harmless things for being who you are

02:08:51.840 --> 02:08:59.120
[Guest]: I think both at the individual level at the family level and at the national level wherever you face

02:08:59.120 --> 02:09:10.160
[Guest]: a certain amount of hostility for being different or just being you know that that is I don't know

02:09:10.160 --> 02:09:17.840
[Guest]: what the opposite of home is I guess not quite home or whatever yeah you know that that's and

02:09:17.840 --> 02:09:23.200
[Amit Varma]: it also strikes me you know you've written elsewhere about there's this great quote by

02:09:23.200 --> 02:09:28.160
[Amit Varma]: you about what your claim to India is in your words and of course your mother is an Indian

02:09:28.160 --> 02:09:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Muslim your father was a Hindu who came from Pakistan and at one point you write quote I

02:09:33.920 --> 02:09:39.520
[Amit Varma]: don't say it though I don't want to make any claims upon India through appeals to Hindu ancestry the

02:09:39.520 --> 02:09:43.840
[Amit Varma]: stronger claim is that of Muslims who chose not to leave when presented with the choice

02:09:43.840 --> 02:09:48.720
[Amit Varma]: resisting majoritarianism I genuinely believe is the highest form of patriotism stop quote and this

02:09:48.720 --> 02:09:54.000
[Amit Varma]: is a point in a episode last year couple couple comedy also made that if you think about who are

02:09:54.000 --> 02:09:58.640
[Amit Varma]: truly patriotic it's not the Hindus who stayed by default necessarily because they didn't have to do

02:09:58.640 --> 02:10:03.680
[Amit Varma]: anything it's the Muslims who chose to stay and what you were just saying thinking aloud it also

02:10:03.680 --> 02:10:09.040
[Amit Varma]: strikes me that all the Muslims who left did not in a sense leave home it's just that they suddenly

02:10:09.040 --> 02:10:14.720
[Amit Varma]: had no home because the notion of safety is tied up with home with the way you're defining home

02:10:14.720 --> 02:10:21.760
[Amit Varma]: and that kind of you know went away with them and in these present times where you know we've spoken

02:10:21.760 --> 02:10:26.960
[Amit Varma]: about all of the politics you know coming from language and the way you know Urdu is associated

02:10:26.960 --> 02:10:34.320
[Amit Varma]: with Muslims and suddenly go to Pakistan is you know something that is hurled at us so often

02:10:34.320 --> 02:10:38.640
[Amit Varma]: you know I go back to your quote that you know as much as home is a place of safety it is also

02:10:38.640 --> 02:10:44.560
[Amit Varma]: a place where you are visible stop code and the very sad question that struck me then is it then

02:10:44.560 --> 02:10:50.160
[Amit Varma]: becoming very hard for Muslims to feel at home in India today the way it is because those layers of

02:10:50.160 --> 02:10:55.280
[Amit Varma]: whatever safety that you had are being stripped away I mean it's not necessarily something new

02:10:55.280 --> 02:11:00.560
[Amit Varma]: our culture has been like this forever you know things like love jihad and cow slaughter were

02:11:00.560 --> 02:11:06.080
[Amit Varma]: issues back in the 1920s as well as Akshay Mukul writes in his excellent book on the Gita Press

02:11:06.080 --> 02:11:10.960
[Amit Varma]: it's it's been there these are strains but obviously these strains have come to the surface

02:11:12.560 --> 02:11:18.480
[Amit Varma]: you know and and it's gained more than sort of it's not just part of the culture it's politically

02:11:19.280 --> 02:11:26.080
[Amit Varma]: dominant you've written in your book also about how it's so hard for Muslims to sort of get homes

02:11:26.080 --> 02:11:32.400
[Amit Varma]: in Bombay a struggle that you know you face being Muslim woman and single and all of those all those

02:11:32.400 --> 02:11:39.200
[Amit Varma]: multiple strikes against you so what are your evolving feelings on this because this is something

02:11:39.200 --> 02:11:44.640
[Amit Varma]: that to someone like me it is not visceral I can think about it at an intellectual level

02:11:44.640 --> 02:11:50.080
[Amit Varma]: but it is not visceral because I am not in danger right but for someone like you it's different so

02:11:50.080 --> 02:11:56.640
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about how you're thinking on this is kind of evolved and where you see hope if

02:11:56.640 --> 02:12:03.600
[Guest]: any well I'm always very reluctant to speak for other people I think this is one of the reasons

02:12:03.600 --> 02:12:09.440
[Guest]: why I write so many personal essays and memoir and things because I always resist the urge to

02:12:10.000 --> 02:12:15.520
[Guest]: speak for you know a community or the nation or write the big India book or whatever it is

02:12:18.240 --> 02:12:25.360
[Guest]: speaking for myself I think certainly there is some degree of insecurity and I think more than

02:12:25.360 --> 02:12:32.160
[Guest]: anything else the reason there were so many people protesting against an RCC etc was that it was the

02:12:32.160 --> 02:12:38.240
[Guest]: first time in the language of law there was some discrimination enshrined I mean there was there

02:12:38.240 --> 02:12:43.040
[Guest]: was no other problem with you know refugees from anywhere being in the country and they could

02:12:43.680 --> 02:12:47.280
[Guest]: could be easily Hindu refugees from Bangladesh or Pakistan or whatever

02:12:48.800 --> 02:12:54.480
[Guest]: but there is no reason to assume that Muslims in Pakistan are not under attack and they are

02:12:54.480 --> 02:13:00.720
[Guest]: minorities in Pakistan and not just Hindus the Christians and the Muslims the Shias the Ahmadi

02:13:00.720 --> 02:13:06.560
[Guest]: they are also under attack and this is the first time that specifically implicitly there was a

02:13:06.560 --> 02:13:13.440
[Guest]: discrimination made in law which I think made it extremely problematic because once you lose

02:13:13.440 --> 02:13:19.680
[Guest]: citizenship you know this is the beginning of the loss of citizenship or at least the beginning of

02:13:19.680 --> 02:13:25.760
[Guest]: of discriminatory laws which will then expose you to a lot of harassment

02:13:27.040 --> 02:13:32.000
[Guest]: where you're constantly having to prove you know some by way of paperwork or some other way

02:13:33.280 --> 02:13:40.000
[Guest]: that you belong I think starting from there certainly people are very concerned I won't

02:13:40.000 --> 02:13:46.560
[Guest]: say that they don't feel at home I don't know if because speaking for myself I can just say

02:13:46.560 --> 02:13:52.640
[Guest]: that this is what I know that this this is home because it always has been and I don't know of

02:13:52.640 --> 02:14:00.160
[Guest]: any other home or any other place where I'd rather be in that sense and I think all the Muslims that

02:14:00.160 --> 02:14:05.520
[Guest]: I know at least even the ones who are very vocal and very critical one of the reasons they are that

02:14:05.520 --> 02:14:12.480
[Guest]: vocal and that critical and a lot of them are relatively privileged you know it's not that it

02:14:12.480 --> 02:14:18.560
[Guest]: is inconceivable for them a life elsewhere the reason that they criticize is because it matters

02:14:18.560 --> 02:14:24.560
[Guest]: so much to them that they be here that that their affection not be challenged and that the sense of

02:14:24.560 --> 02:14:31.600
[Guest]: belonging not challenged it matters that much which is why you're willing to risk the everything

02:14:31.600 --> 02:14:38.160
[Guest]: else that comes with it the displeasure of the state or whatever it is but I do think that

02:14:38.160 --> 02:14:45.200
[Guest]: speaking for myself I can say this that the fear was also quite real now and part of the reason

02:14:45.200 --> 02:14:52.480
[Guest]: like I said is the law but also that more and more one sees that justice does not actually happen

02:14:53.280 --> 02:15:01.360
[Guest]: where you're seeing a certain difference in the way violence and law enforcement

02:15:01.360 --> 02:15:09.280
[Guest]: unfolds and the ways in which if for example a thief comes right now to my door right what will

02:15:09.280 --> 02:15:16.240
[Guest]: I do I'll call the cops right and I have always all my life believed that the cops are there for

02:15:16.240 --> 02:15:24.400
[Guest]: me right but if in my mind you plant a seed of doubt because of not necessarily one set of cops

02:15:24.400 --> 02:15:29.120
[Guest]: but another set of cops elsewhere having behaved in discriminate-free ways or having said and done

02:15:29.120 --> 02:15:33.360
[Guest]: things that they shouldn't have once you plant that doubt in my head that you can't call the

02:15:33.360 --> 02:15:39.760
[Guest]: cops because of what might happen to you then or because they don't care then you have to live your

02:15:39.760 --> 02:15:44.960
[Guest]: life in different ways right if you start counting upon the state to give you what the state owes

02:15:44.960 --> 02:15:51.840
[Guest]: you then you have a very serious problem on your hands and you have to live your life in a different

02:15:51.840 --> 02:16:00.240
[Guest]: problem on your hands that is I cannot even conceive actually right now what my life might

02:16:00.240 --> 02:16:06.800
[Guest]: be like if I lose that faith and trust completely so far it hasn't been lost completely so far people

02:16:06.800 --> 02:16:12.320
[Guest]: people are new people critique people fight because they haven't yet lost hope once they

02:16:12.320 --> 02:16:19.360
[Guest]: lose hope then there'll be nothing left to talk about yeah and you know as far as the CAA NRC

02:16:19.360 --> 02:16:24.880
[Amit Varma]: is concerned the reason it was such a big deal was you know not just a kind of the letter of

02:16:24.880 --> 02:16:30.320
[Amit Varma]: the law where some people defended it by saying that hey but you know all kinds of specious

02:16:30.320 --> 02:16:35.120
[Amit Varma]: reasonings were given I had a great episode on this with Srinath Raghavan as well but also because

02:16:35.120 --> 02:16:40.400
[Amit Varma]: the intent behind it was explicitly stated you know there are videos of Amit Shah stating at

02:16:40.400 --> 02:16:45.920
[Amit Varma]: election rallies that what would you know happen in Assam after the CAA came into operation and

02:16:45.920 --> 02:16:52.640
[Amit Varma]: all of that so you could say the CAA was part of his toolkit as it were but to sort of get back to

02:16:52.640 --> 02:17:00.640
[Amit Varma]: the subject of all that's you know one of the most striking sentences in your book in fact

02:17:00.640 --> 02:17:06.080
[Amit Varma]: the sentence of the book for me which really struck me was when you wrote quote was partition

02:17:06.080 --> 02:17:13.120
[Amit Varma]: concluded in 1947 or was it initiated stop quote and almost as an elaboration of that there is this

02:17:13.120 --> 02:17:20.000
[Amit Varma]: wonderful quote by Maulana Azad where he wrote at the time quote it was being openly said in

02:17:20.000 --> 02:17:24.640
[Amit Varma]: congress circles that Hindus and Pakistan's need not have any fears as there would be four and a

02:17:24.640 --> 02:17:29.840
[Amit Varma]: half crores of Muslims in India and if there was any oppression of Hindus in Pakistan then Muslims

02:17:29.840 --> 02:17:34.720
[Amit Varma]: in India would have to bear the consequences stop quote and after quoting him you said well they are

02:17:34.720 --> 02:17:40.320
[Amit Varma]: right so in a sense just looking back on history and all your readings of it and

02:17:40.320 --> 02:17:44.640
[Amit Varma]: sort of what you've seen around you would you say that in a sense there is a historical

02:17:44.640 --> 02:17:51.840
[Amit Varma]: inevitability I mean nothing is inevitable of course but were the currents moving in this

02:17:51.840 --> 02:17:57.920
[Amit Varma]: really sad direction anyway from back then because everything that is playing out now is not something

02:17:57.920 --> 02:18:03.840
[Amit Varma]: new that has happened not some you know quantum leap of events this whole movement as you know

02:18:03.840 --> 02:18:10.400
[Amit Varma]: movement as you know historians like Akshay Mukhulev and Akar himself in his recent book have sort of

02:18:10.400 --> 02:18:16.400
[Amit Varma]: documented it's been playing out for a long long time and it's been coming to this so one of the

02:18:16.400 --> 02:18:23.440
[Guest]: things Amit is that I am fundamentally against theocracies I do not believe in theocracies I do

02:18:23.440 --> 02:18:30.560
[Guest]: not think they are sustainable over any length of time and I do not think that any country that

02:18:30.560 --> 02:18:39.920
[Guest]: defines itself solely on religious lines can hope to be a properly functional country I mean it's

02:18:39.920 --> 02:18:45.200
[Guest]: not like countries haven't defined themselves in religious terms before you know but they haven't

02:18:45.200 --> 02:18:51.440
[Guest]: defined themselves solely in religious terms and I think it's been very rare in society where

02:18:51.440 --> 02:18:57.680
[Guest]: partitions have happened like national partitions entire countries separating only on the grounds of

02:18:57.680 --> 02:19:03.680
[Guest]: religion there are usually some other factors involved so there have been many kind of separatist

02:19:03.680 --> 02:19:08.240
[Guest]: movements elsewhere sometimes it's about power political power sometimes it's about language and

02:19:08.240 --> 02:19:15.760
[Guest]: culture and all of these are different facets of religion sometimes religion is used to kind of as a

02:19:15.760 --> 02:19:22.400
[Guest]: tool to with which to extend your own political power like starting from crusades etc down you

02:19:22.400 --> 02:19:28.160
[Guest]: know like turkey and the institution of the caliph etc etc all of these there was religious

02:19:28.160 --> 02:19:38.080
[Guest]: power invested in rulers but there was never a time where any any prosperous good healthy society

02:19:39.520 --> 02:19:44.560
[Guest]: chose to define itself in exclusionary terms that we are this because we are not that

02:19:44.560 --> 02:19:50.800
[Guest]: I think the problem began in India in South Asia particularly at this time because the moment you

02:19:50.800 --> 02:19:58.160
[Guest]: say that you know that that you can conceive of a nation or that you can conceive of national

02:19:58.160 --> 02:20:05.120
[Guest]: boundaries as countries not on linguistic terms not on cultural terms not as geographic entities

02:20:05.120 --> 02:20:10.160
[Guest]: that you know a solid mass of people who happen to be living together in the same geography

02:20:10.160 --> 02:20:17.440
[Guest]: the moment you say that we define ourselves as x as separate from y the moment that happened

02:20:17.440 --> 02:20:23.440
[Guest]: whether it was one bunch of people doing it or it was another bunch of people doing it it was the

02:20:23.440 --> 02:20:28.480
[Guest]: muslim league whether it was the early thinkers some people say the earliest proponents of the

02:20:28.480 --> 02:20:35.600
[Guest]: two-nation theory were also the proponents of modern hindutva if you begin to define yourself

02:20:35.600 --> 02:20:41.840
[Guest]: as that which you are not you will always have trouble defining who you are and you will always

02:20:41.840 --> 02:20:48.320
[Guest]: find the other within the other within the other like in Pakistan soon after partition that you

02:20:48.320 --> 02:20:53.600
[Guest]: know the problems with the Ahmadi started because you decided that yes we are an islamic country but

02:20:53.600 --> 02:21:00.240
[Guest]: they are not muslims let us not uh you know so of course there will be some oppression of minorities

02:21:00.240 --> 02:21:05.840
[Guest]: uh you know so of course there will be some oppression of minorities but you will also constantly create

02:21:05.840 --> 02:21:12.400
[Guest]: new minorities and when the oppression of the old minorities gets boring then you find

02:21:13.280 --> 02:21:20.640
[Guest]: new ways to focus on you know appropriation or marginalization and we are seeing that Pakistan

02:21:20.640 --> 02:21:25.840
[Guest]: is suffering uh the consequences of of uh it's not just the minorities that suffer the country

02:21:25.840 --> 02:21:31.440
[Guest]: as a whole suffers right because conflict is conflict conflict cannot exist as a one-way

02:21:31.440 --> 02:21:37.840
[Guest]: street that's inevitable and added to that there are all the other problems so it's not like you

02:21:37.840 --> 02:21:42.880
[Guest]: replace one set of problems with another I think this is also the problem with India and India would

02:21:42.880 --> 02:21:49.920
[Guest]: absolutely should have taken its lesson uh seeing that you know everything that has happened

02:21:50.800 --> 02:21:54.800
[Guest]: in Pakistan seeing that this has happened we should have taken our lesson and

02:21:54.800 --> 02:22:01.520
[Guest]: course corrected in some fashion and actively stopped trying to define ourselves as we are not

02:22:01.520 --> 02:22:06.640
[Guest]: Pakistan that is the entire national identity cannot be reduced to that okay you're not Pakistan

02:22:06.640 --> 02:22:12.880
[Guest]: but you're not China either you're not even Sri Lanka you're not even Nepal come on so um they

02:22:12.880 --> 02:22:20.880
[Guest]: want to be Nepal well Nepal very strongly feels that it would not like to be India so uh I I think

02:22:20.880 --> 02:22:28.960
[Guest]: there's a bit of a problem there and and I I do think that it is quite dangerous to press on with

02:22:28.960 --> 02:22:33.440
[Guest]: this kind of because you know if you thought that you could have gotten rid of the Muslims by

02:22:33.440 --> 02:22:38.880
[Guest]: creating Pakistan and then later Bangladesh then you say okay there's there's still a few more left

02:22:38.880 --> 02:22:45.120
[Guest]: we'll just get rid of them in other ways uh whether it's through you know marginalization or

02:22:45.120 --> 02:22:52.720
[Guest]: you know in political trying to find political solutions or then then what it doesn't take long

02:22:52.720 --> 02:22:58.480
[Guest]: in Pakistan it didn't even take it's taken less than 50 years from the focus to shift from uh

02:22:59.200 --> 02:23:05.360
[Guest]: the Hindus and the Christians as the other to the Shia which is a very large minority you know it's

02:23:05.360 --> 02:23:10.400
[Guest]: not a small minority in Pakistan and uh and they have other problems on their hands they have the

02:23:10.400 --> 02:23:16.400
[Guest]: Baloch problem they have this problem that problem poverty unemployment all of those problems um

02:23:17.440 --> 02:23:24.160
[Guest]: I just feel that what happens in in situations like this I haven't read enough historically

02:23:24.160 --> 02:23:30.000
[Guest]: but I think what happens is that you ultimately run out of others and you run out of political

02:23:30.000 --> 02:23:36.000
[Guest]: solutions to try and address the otherization of minorities and sooner or later someone steps in

02:23:36.000 --> 02:23:41.120
[Guest]: to take advantage of your inner chaos it could be an economic advantage it could be a political

02:23:41.120 --> 02:23:46.240
[Guest]: advantage it is inevitable so India should be on its guard not to allow that to happen.

02:23:47.120 --> 02:23:52.160
[Amit Varma]: Couple of great insights sir which I'll unpack one is of course the exclusionary aspect of it like

02:23:52.160 --> 02:23:56.960
[Amit Varma]: uh when I did an episode with Akar on this a couple of years back in fact he pointed out that

02:23:56.960 --> 02:24:02.320
[Amit Varma]: you know what is this Hindu nation really all about all it is is exclusionary it doesn't define

02:24:02.320 --> 02:24:07.840
[Amit Varma]: itself in positive terms like we shall only do this or we shall only do that but in negative

02:24:07.840 --> 02:24:13.040
[Amit Varma]: terms like right down to the language right down to the movement that we shall uh you know Hindustani

02:24:13.040 --> 02:24:18.240
[Amit Varma]: isn't good because there are Persian influences we shall build a Hindu without Persian or you know

02:24:18.240 --> 02:24:22.800
[Amit Varma]: love jihad is exclusionary the laws against cow slaughter obviously we know whether where they

02:24:22.800 --> 02:24:27.760
[Amit Varma]: are targeted so they are exclusionary this whole Pakistan thing is exclusionary so that's a great

02:24:27.760 --> 02:24:34.480
[Amit Varma]: point the other sort of great insight which seems to be the insight of the month on this show is

02:24:34.480 --> 02:24:41.600
[Amit Varma]: what you sort of referred to about finding new others like last week I had Raghu Sanjalal Jaitley

02:24:41.600 --> 02:24:47.120
[Amit Varma]: on the show very fine public intellectual and that's a pseudonym of course and Raghu spoke

02:24:47.120 --> 02:24:53.520
[Amit Varma]: about Carl Schmitt's concept of politics requiring an enemy where the idea is that you always require

02:24:53.520 --> 02:25:01.120
[Amit Varma]: an enemy to do politics and so eventually even if you manage to for example whoever is your core

02:25:01.120 --> 02:25:05.760
[Amit Varma]: enemy now if you get rid of them you will find another enemy from within and you will keep

02:25:05.760 --> 02:25:11.200
[Amit Varma]: splintering and keep splintering and keep splintering till till there is sort of no further

02:25:11.200 --> 02:25:18.080
[Amit Varma]: to go and and one does sort of see this playing out within the Hindu right wing even now where

02:25:18.080 --> 02:25:23.760
[Amit Varma]: there are these internecine little wars developing so even in a hypothetical thought experiment where

02:25:23.760 --> 02:25:28.960
[Amit Varma]: you could magically suddenly all the Muslims of India could be put in Pakistan even if you could

02:25:28.960 --> 02:25:34.080
[Amit Varma]: do that I don't think that would solve anything it would probably make things much worse which is

02:25:34.080 --> 02:25:40.400
[Amit Varma]: anyway a crazy thought experiment so yeah so it's it's but I don't I don't know where it ends up

02:25:40.400 --> 02:25:45.760
[Amit Varma]: because I don't think we have enough of a sample size of these situations playing out in history

02:25:45.760 --> 02:25:50.080
[Amit Varma]: to know where we are going you know my earlier sense was that look it's going to get better

02:25:50.080 --> 02:25:54.880
[Amit Varma]: but it's going to get worse before it gets better so you have to be patient and wait it out but when

02:25:54.880 --> 02:26:01.520
[Amit Varma]: I try to think about scenarios in which it gets better it's really hard to come up with stuff

02:26:01.520 --> 02:26:08.480
[Amit Varma]: let's move away from religion for a moment and talk about another major fissure within this

02:26:08.480 --> 02:26:12.880
[Amit Varma]: country as it were now just yesterday or day before there was this ridiculous court judgment

02:26:12.880 --> 02:26:18.400
[Amit Varma]: I came across on Twitter where a minor girl had been repeatedly raped by someone and the court

02:26:18.400 --> 02:26:24.800
[Amit Varma]: to asked her rapist do you agree to be her husband right and this is of course that age-old thing of

02:26:24.800 --> 02:26:30.240
[Amit Varma]: women being looked upon as a property of men which is enshrined in the Indian laws by the way I read

02:26:30.240 --> 02:26:35.600
[Amit Varma]: episodes on this as well and you know even culturally like one of the heroes of the Hindu

02:26:35.600 --> 02:26:41.120
[Amit Varma]: right wing is a guy called Karpatri Maharaj so he wrote this really interesting book called

02:26:41.120 --> 02:26:46.160
[Amit Varma]: I forget what it's called but it it's something versus Ram Rajya I think it compares communism

02:26:46.160 --> 02:26:51.360
[Amit Varma]: to Ram Rajya and there he says the reason communism can't work is because there is

02:26:51.360 --> 02:26:56.800
[Amit Varma]: no notion of property automatically every woman therefore does not belong to anyone

02:26:56.800 --> 02:27:01.600
[Amit Varma]: and she becomes a bucket from which any man can drink more or less quote unquote right

02:27:01.600 --> 02:27:06.320
[Amit Varma]: which tells you how so many people think of women that they are the property of men so if

02:27:06.320 --> 02:27:11.600
[Amit Varma]: a woman has been defiled as property then the rapist needs to make it good to her by

02:27:11.600 --> 02:27:16.800
[Amit Varma]: adapting her now you've sort of written about this in pretty strong terms yourself in your

02:27:16.800 --> 02:27:22.240
[Amit Varma]: chapter called outsiders at home where at one point you've written quote there was little

02:27:22.240 --> 02:27:27.040
[Amit Varma]: difference between a wife and a slave in the sense that both were uprooted physically and psychology

02:27:27.040 --> 02:27:32.240
[Amit Varma]: a woman's sexual choice was easily overridden she didn't control the fruits of her labor

02:27:32.240 --> 02:27:36.400
[Amit Varma]: and just like slaves couldn't leave it was not for nothing that wives in many cultures referred

02:27:36.400 --> 02:27:40.800
[Amit Varma]: to husbands as lord and master stop quote and of course you back it up with a whole bunch of

02:27:40.800 --> 02:27:47.680
[Amit Varma]: statistics like you know the human development survey in 2016 which found that 74 percent of

02:27:47.680 --> 02:27:52.880
[Amit Varma]: Indian women need permission from parents husband or in-laws to step out of the house even just to

02:27:52.880 --> 02:27:59.440
[Amit Varma]: see a doctor and only five percent felt they had any real control over who they would get married

02:27:59.440 --> 02:28:03.040
[Amit Varma]: to which you know seems a very real picture you know many of the people listening to this might

02:28:03.040 --> 02:28:08.640
[Amit Varma]: be in privileged situations where they don't see this around them but these figures ring real and

02:28:08.640 --> 02:28:13.200
[Amit Varma]: you've written a lot about this now you know just looking at what's been happening over the last

02:28:13.200 --> 02:28:19.120
[Amit Varma]: few years one there has been a sense that people are making more noise about this you know you had

02:28:19.120 --> 02:28:24.640
[Amit Varma]: the nirbhaya case you had you know me too breaking twice here not that anything happened to any of

02:28:24.640 --> 02:28:32.320
[Amit Varma]: those men but at least in the rhetoric in public you see this being spoken about more but are things

02:28:32.320 --> 02:28:36.960
[Amit Varma]: really changing on the ground what is your sense of it as someone who's been writing about it and

02:28:36.960 --> 02:28:43.840
[Guest]: covering it for so long my sense amit is that they are changing and they aren't changing so they are

02:28:43.840 --> 02:28:50.320
[Guest]: changing in the sense that compared to you need something to compare it to right so from everything

02:28:50.320 --> 02:28:56.880
[Guest]: i've read and even from what i remember seeing i look around me in the urban context and i see that

02:28:56.880 --> 02:29:03.680
[Guest]: things are different from what they were say 20 years ago or when i was a child or or from what

02:29:03.680 --> 02:29:09.760
[Guest]: i've read in in you know literature of the late 19th and early 20th century so some things have

02:29:09.760 --> 02:29:16.320
[Guest]: changed just in terms of the education statistics right you look at the education statistics since

02:29:16.320 --> 02:29:21.360
[Guest]: india won independence and you will see that for both men and women that education is much more

02:29:21.360 --> 02:29:26.480
[Guest]: widely available literacy is much more widely available even from when i wrote my first book

02:29:26.480 --> 02:29:33.120
[Guest]: where i was saying that i i did the math and said that i i must be one maybe amongst the top one or

02:29:33.120 --> 02:29:39.760
[Guest]: two percent just on the basis that i do have some postgraduate education forget my income just the

02:29:39.760 --> 02:29:46.400
[Guest]: fact that i studied that much places me in a position of great privilege i think even from there

02:29:46.400 --> 02:29:52.240
[Guest]: even from 15 years ago things have changed a lot significantly many more women graduates the

02:29:52.240 --> 02:29:57.600
[Guest]: average age of marriage has gone up it used to be somewhere between 18 and 20 it is now closer to

02:29:57.600 --> 02:30:04.320
[Guest]: inching towards 22 which is above 21 and that is i think a very positive sign and i think if you

02:30:04.320 --> 02:30:09.440
[Guest]: compare it to 100 years ago i mean when there were girls who were being married at eight and nine

02:30:09.440 --> 02:30:17.280
[Guest]: and ten and i think at 13 girls were considered too old to wed and from there to where we are now

02:30:17.280 --> 02:30:25.920
[Guest]: i would say that so much has changed a lot has not changed when it comes to safety and the reason it

02:30:25.920 --> 02:30:31.200
[Guest]: hasn't changed is because i was just having this conversation actually earlier in the day with

02:30:31.200 --> 02:30:36.160
[Guest]: another woman but she refused to talk about feminism you know in the context of some seminar

02:30:36.160 --> 02:30:41.120
[Guest]: women's day something and she says that we have enough feminism women know what they want etc

02:30:41.120 --> 02:30:47.040
[Guest]: etc the problem is that we have no conversations about men and masculinity we have so many

02:30:47.040 --> 02:30:52.720
[Guest]: conversations about women and feminism but we do not men are not taught to think differently

02:30:53.280 --> 02:30:57.760
[Guest]: they are not to change anything women are constantly being taught to change things

02:30:57.760 --> 02:31:02.320
[Guest]: to break the ceiling and to shatter that stereotype and so on so the men are not

02:31:02.320 --> 02:31:09.040
[Guest]: shattering anything maybe a very small handful of i mean apologies to you of course i'm sure you are

02:31:09.600 --> 02:31:22.960
[Guest]: but in general by and large and and there is so much of a tendency to lord men for simply

02:31:22.960 --> 02:31:29.040
[Guest]: acknowledging women as being full human beings and and we are so busy doing that at the moment

02:31:29.040 --> 02:31:36.320
[Guest]: that and this is not true only of india by the way i read a lot of say blogs and conversations

02:31:36.320 --> 02:31:43.360
[Guest]: in australia in the west in america in the usa you have these conversations outrageous conversations

02:31:43.360 --> 02:31:49.120
[Guest]: where a woman gets raped or whatever or she accuses a man of rape and the only conversation

02:31:49.120 --> 02:31:53.920
[Guest]: there is that oh he's an athlete and he'll lose a year and his life will be ruined and

02:31:53.920 --> 02:32:00.320
[Guest]: ruined and you can't wrap your mind around that right that we are in this day and age even in the

02:32:00.320 --> 02:32:05.520
[Guest]: so-called quote-unquote developed countries that this conversation is is unfolding and that it's

02:32:05.520 --> 02:32:13.520
[Guest]: real but it is um i think that one of the things is that uh we haven't we haven't started talking

02:32:13.520 --> 02:32:17.920
[Guest]: about it and i think we really need to start talking about the reasons why we don't talk about

02:32:17.920 --> 02:32:25.520
[Guest]: it about the bodily integrity of women the absolute and full autonomy not just sexual autonomy but the

02:32:25.520 --> 02:32:32.720
[Guest]: absolute physical autonomy that is due to women and all conversations kind of come to a halt around

02:32:32.720 --> 02:32:38.400
[Guest]: this partly because the general fear of any sexual talk like in india the government and i i don't

02:32:38.400 --> 02:32:44.240
[Guest]: think it's just this government it's all successive and previous governments over the last whatever

02:32:44.240 --> 02:32:52.960
[Guest]: number of years refuse to have sex education in schools high school students i mean and the age

02:32:52.960 --> 02:32:58.720
[Guest]: of consent legally is 16 so at 16 you should be able to not only have knowledge but also

02:33:00.560 --> 02:33:08.000
[Guest]: be able to discuss these things in class at home these conversations by and large i think if at all

02:33:08.000 --> 02:33:13.520
[Guest]: they unfold they happen maybe for five maybe not even one percent of the population actually i

02:33:13.520 --> 02:33:20.960
[Guest]: think the other thing is that while we give women freedoms the whole idea is give women freedoms

02:33:20.960 --> 02:33:28.720
[Guest]: like girls are given more freedom now uh language language so the whole thing is nobody talks about

02:33:28.720 --> 02:33:35.360
[Guest]: giving boys freedom sometimes you give children freedom in general children again are property

02:33:35.360 --> 02:33:43.840
[Guest]: in the way that women are still seen as some kind of acquisition the other is that we do not

02:33:43.840 --> 02:33:52.560
[Guest]: talk about because women being women and the way that your biology works because you are the one

02:33:52.560 --> 02:33:57.520
[Guest]: that gives birth to children i think a lot of the conversation dies down when it comes to this

02:33:57.520 --> 02:34:04.400
[Guest]: question of children where there is this reluctance to acknowledge that the reason why you do not want

02:34:04.400 --> 02:34:09.840
[Guest]: to give full bodily autonomy to women or to consider their consent is because then you will

02:34:09.840 --> 02:34:15.200
[Guest]: also have to consider the fact that what she does with her body including childbirth and and what

02:34:15.200 --> 02:34:20.400
[Guest]: she does with the children after that is also her decision completely and that you have either a

02:34:20.400 --> 02:34:27.280
[Guest]: minor role to play or no role to play at all and uh this is something that no society is willing

02:34:27.280 --> 02:34:32.320
[Guest]: to acknowledge not just india i think the west particularly too they do not want to acknowledge

02:34:32.320 --> 02:34:38.160
[Guest]: the fact that if you allow women full bodily autonomy then you lose control over the children

02:34:38.160 --> 02:34:43.280
[Guest]: that she will produce and it's an ancient ancient thing actually this is the fundamental

02:34:43.280 --> 02:34:49.040
[Guest]: civilizational question starting from i don't know biblical or even before that whatever that

02:34:49.040 --> 02:34:55.520
[Guest]: whatever that era was before that this is it's at the heart of all systems this is where matriarchy

02:34:55.520 --> 02:35:02.320
[Guest]: shifted to patriarchy that the control of the children the fruit of the womb because finally i

02:35:02.320 --> 02:35:08.480
[Guest]: read this very interesting thing that when a woman gives birth they call it labor right she labors

02:35:08.480 --> 02:35:14.000
[Guest]: it is she who labors it is the fruit of her labors it is not the fruit of your labors

02:35:14.560 --> 02:35:22.880
[Guest]: so who then controls the children who owns the children so to speak uh i think fundamentally

02:35:22.880 --> 02:35:27.520
[Guest]: you cut away everything else it all comes down to that and all violence targeted at women

02:35:27.520 --> 02:35:32.720
[Guest]: is ultimately targeted at controlling who she will birth and what she will do with those children

02:35:33.840 --> 02:35:37.920
[Amit Varma]: fascinating and what's also ironic here is you know we were talking about colonialism earlier

02:35:37.920 --> 02:35:43.280
[Amit Varma]: and a lot of this prudery around sex education and all that is really uh you know was given to

02:35:43.280 --> 02:35:49.040
[Amit Varma]: us by the british with the victorian morality and you know it we weren't all you know as our

02:35:49.040 --> 02:35:55.120
[Amit Varma]: ancient cave sculpture show we weren't always this uh prudish uh but we were always pretty

