[Amit Varma]: misogynist but you know leaving that aside let's move into as we reach the last part of the show

02:36:02.240 --> 02:36:09.280
[Amit Varma]: uh let me sort of talk about some of the themes that my listeners are always interested in which

02:36:09.280 --> 02:36:13.920
[Amit Varma]: is for example reading how do we read more what do we read and i thought it's a particularly

02:36:13.920 --> 02:36:19.120
[Amit Varma]: pertinent question to ask you because many years ago you put together this anthology called unbound

02:36:19.120 --> 02:36:25.040
[Amit Varma]: which was writings of indian women through the ages fantastic anthology and you mentioned in

02:36:25.040 --> 02:36:29.520
[Amit Varma]: an interview that when it came to you when you were the publisher came to you you said no i'm

02:36:29.520 --> 02:36:33.920
[Amit Varma]: not an expert i'm not an academic i don't want to do this but she insisted and you said okay let me

02:36:33.920 --> 02:36:39.600
[Amit Varma]: give it a go and then you started reading madly and discovered much more than you thought you had

02:36:39.600 --> 02:36:44.880
[Amit Varma]: and of course one of the things that struck with me was the story you told about this uh early 19th

02:36:44.880 --> 02:36:51.360
[Amit Varma]: century lady called rasundhara devi who you know got married at eight had kids knew the letters of

02:36:51.360 --> 02:36:56.240
[Amit Varma]: the alphabet but wasn't allowed to read and she was in the kitchen all day and all she wanted to

02:36:56.240 --> 02:37:01.440
[Amit Varma]: do was read and she wasn't allowed and then one day she kind of she dreamt about reading she wanted

02:37:01.440 --> 02:37:07.600
[Amit Varma]: it so badly and then she would there was a book which was you know a series of sort of little

02:37:07.600 --> 02:37:13.920
[Amit Varma]: slices of wood a sort of proto paper perhaps and from that book she would take one page at a time

02:37:13.920 --> 02:37:20.240
[Amit Varma]: hide it in a box of atta and sort of read when she could and eventually she wrote this autobiography

02:37:20.240 --> 02:37:25.440
[Amit Varma]: called amar jeebon but that's a digression and i found it a delightful story so i had to repeat it

02:37:25.440 --> 02:37:29.840
[Amit Varma]: for my listeners but my question to you is this that clearly what you mentioned is that when you

02:37:29.840 --> 02:37:35.200
[Amit Varma]: were doing the reading for this book it wasn't reading you would ordinarily have done you did

02:37:35.200 --> 02:37:40.000
[Amit Varma]: it for the purpose of this book and it expanded your mind in certain ways and just as you know

02:37:40.000 --> 02:37:43.600
[Amit Varma]: we were talking earlier about how the form that you write in can shape the content can shape the

02:37:43.600 --> 02:37:49.040
[Amit Varma]: person here the reading you are doing is also kind of shaping you and in this case it was an

02:37:49.040 --> 02:37:54.400
[Amit Varma]: assignment which came to you and you chose to do it but if one is to say to oneself that look i

02:37:54.400 --> 02:38:00.480
[Amit Varma]: want to expand my knowledge of the world how do i do this you know reading in an arbitrary uh sort

02:38:00.480 --> 02:38:06.800
[Amit Varma]: of way may not kind of get me there do you think that there is then value to building a sort of

02:38:06.800 --> 02:38:12.160
[Amit Varma]: program for yourself even if you're not say putting together an anthology just to educate yourself and

02:38:12.160 --> 02:38:18.640
[Amit Varma]: also what is the value of uh reading to you like you know i always say that if i read different

02:38:18.640 --> 02:38:23.280
[Amit Varma]: books all my life i would be a different person completely so what does reading mean to you in

02:38:23.280 --> 02:38:28.080
[Amit Varma]: that sense and what advice would you give to people who want to read more but don't quite know

02:38:28.080 --> 02:38:34.880
[Guest]: what or how to go about it i completely agree with you on that last bit i mean if if i had read

02:38:34.880 --> 02:38:39.920
[Guest]: completely differently i think i would have been a different person too and thank you for all the

02:38:39.920 --> 02:38:46.160
[Guest]: nice things you said about that anthology i think for me that doing that book was completely

02:38:46.160 --> 02:38:53.520
[Guest]: transformative um it it came to me as an offer to do this and i was very reluctant um i think

02:38:53.520 --> 02:38:58.560
[Guest]: one of the things with me is also that i don't like to do things badly so once i said yes i said

02:38:58.560 --> 02:39:03.680
[Guest]: okay now i i will not do the lazy thing i'm not going to look at 10 different anthologies and see

02:39:03.680 --> 02:39:09.600
[Guest]: what other people have done and cherry pick right because i was doing a selection i wasn't doing

02:39:09.600 --> 02:39:15.520
[Guest]: everything but i did decide to read everything i could find in order to make a proper selection

02:39:16.080 --> 02:39:21.440
[Guest]: so it took me ultimately almost three and a half years from the start of the project to

02:39:21.440 --> 02:39:27.440
[Guest]: its publication i read everything i could find by written by an indian woman in english translation

02:39:28.720 --> 02:39:35.200
[Guest]: and obviously while i not entirely but i would say that i read for three years almost exclusively

02:39:35.200 --> 02:39:41.600
[Guest]: women and that for me really was transformative more than anything else it completely broke down

02:39:41.600 --> 02:39:48.560
[Guest]: every bias i had about what one about what powerful literature was i had these stereotypes

02:39:48.560 --> 02:39:53.280
[Guest]: in my own head and i didn't know that i had them you know that that you think that this is

02:39:53.280 --> 02:39:58.000
[Guest]: interesting or not interesting or this is powerful or this is not powerful or that this is political

02:39:58.000 --> 02:40:03.920
[Guest]: or not political or merely domestic or merely romantic i learned to find the political in

02:40:03.920 --> 02:40:09.920
[Guest]: everything that women said it did and wrote the act of travel could be a highly political act

02:40:09.920 --> 02:40:16.960
[Guest]: highly act of great performative assertion of of absolute equality and freedom i learned all of

02:40:16.960 --> 02:40:25.920
[Guest]: that um and for me that opened up lots of windows in my own head and gave me restored to me also a

02:40:25.920 --> 02:40:32.000
[Guest]: sense of history so i wasn't reading only it was reading a lot of fiction a lot of poetry but even

02:40:32.000 --> 02:40:37.360
[Guest]: within that there is history and it gave me a sense of where indian women come from when we

02:40:37.360 --> 02:40:42.560
[Guest]: say something today we say it because we've been saying something else for the last hundred years

02:40:42.560 --> 02:40:49.280
[Guest]: or we've been saying the same thing for the last 2000 years and nobody listens so i think all those

02:40:49.280 --> 02:40:54.560
[Guest]: different things for me were very transformative and i think that as advice to people i think one

02:40:54.560 --> 02:40:59.600
[Guest]: of the things you can do is to undertake challenges of the sort like like people say feminize your

02:40:59.600 --> 02:41:06.320
[Guest]: canon or decolonize your canon i think there is some merit to that i have read i think after doing

02:41:06.320 --> 02:41:10.560
[Guest]: the book after about three years i took a deep breath and i said okay i should start reading men

02:41:10.560 --> 02:41:18.800
[Guest]: again can't exclusively read women forever i think i still lean more towards uh where fiction is

02:41:18.800 --> 02:41:24.320
[Guest]: concerned i find myself now leaning more and this is this is something that has happened now it it

02:41:24.320 --> 02:41:31.920
[Guest]: wasn't true of me before as a reader but i find that i end up reading a lot more women's fiction

02:41:31.920 --> 02:41:40.800
[Guest]: and i enjoy it in different ways now not to say that i don't enjoy men writing fiction just that i

02:41:40.800 --> 02:41:47.600
[Guest]: find that i think earlier without knowing it i had this inherent bias against fiction by women i

02:41:47.600 --> 02:41:53.760
[Guest]: thought of it as more limited and i think now i'm finally free of that bias so i reach for it more

02:41:53.760 --> 02:42:00.080
[Guest]: often similarly i think i also decided at some point that i will read much more international

02:42:00.080 --> 02:42:08.000
[Guest]: literature i'm still working my way sort of around that i haven't quite succeeded but there is a

02:42:08.000 --> 02:42:12.960
[Guest]: certain bias in the way we receive literature because we read in english we end up reading

02:42:12.960 --> 02:42:18.720
[Guest]: mostly things that are written and published in america and england and a lot of that is written

02:42:18.720 --> 02:42:24.560
[Guest]: by white people and even if it's not written by white people it's written from the western

02:42:24.560 --> 02:42:31.280
[Guest]: perspective you know the western view of the world which is uh both limited and limiting in

02:42:31.280 --> 02:42:37.600
[Guest]: so many ways why should i a reader sitting in india learn to see the way the world looks to

02:42:37.600 --> 02:42:43.440
[Guest]: an american writer in the midwest or whatever it is why should i not learn to see it the way

02:42:44.080 --> 02:42:49.600
[Guest]: it looks from an egyptian perspective or from a syrian perspective or from an african

02:42:49.600 --> 02:42:55.680
[Guest]: and any nigerian perspective or a tunisian perspective why should i not learn to see

02:42:55.680 --> 02:43:00.320
[Guest]: the world in these ways so i think that is something i'm still working on i think it

02:43:00.320 --> 02:43:07.760
[Guest]: does make sense if you can find the time and energy to read in these uh to restrict your

02:43:07.760 --> 02:43:13.840
[Guest]: reading for some time and say that okay for one year only women or for one month only japanese

02:43:13.840 --> 02:43:21.600
[Guest]: writers or for for three months uh only south asian uh writers or or only only

02:43:24.160 --> 02:43:29.040
[Guest]: books about a certain time period so for example i've become very interested in the 19th century

02:43:29.040 --> 02:43:35.360
[Guest]: in india and i keep reaching for books about that because i think also you need to deepen your

02:43:35.360 --> 02:43:42.000
[Guest]: reading you read one book and you feel like you know this i think it's important to also resist

02:43:42.000 --> 02:43:48.800
[Guest]: that and read quite widely about a subject that you feel you know or if you feel strongly about

02:43:48.800 --> 02:43:55.760
[Guest]: something to then read 15 other things around it and see that are your passions rooted in

02:43:55.760 --> 02:44:01.040
[Guest]: something or are they simply rooted in a kind of ignorance these are very wise words and i would

02:44:01.040 --> 02:44:05.600
[Amit Varma]: add to that by telling my listeners that just read one month of any z to start with that's a

02:44:05.600 --> 02:44:10.000
[Amit Varma]: good start and uh what you said about history is also very evocative it reminds me of this quote

02:44:10.000 --> 02:44:14.480
[Amit Varma]: by alan bennett where he was talking about how the history of humanity is a history of the

02:44:14.480 --> 02:44:20.720
[Amit Varma]: inadequacies of men and at one point he wrote quote what is history history is women following

02:44:20.720 --> 02:44:25.680
[Amit Varma]: behind with the bucket stop quote which all indicates a subsidiary role they've been given

02:44:25.680 --> 02:44:30.480
[Amit Varma]: in history the fact that they've had to clean up the mess and it is true that most of what we read

02:44:30.480 --> 02:44:36.400
[Amit Varma]: of history is written by men about men and often for men so i'm going to sort of end this therefore

02:44:36.400 --> 02:44:41.200
[Amit Varma]: with my last question that we all need to expand our gaze we have specific gazes through which we

02:44:41.200 --> 02:44:45.440
[Amit Varma]: look at the world partly determined by our circumstances or whatever our preferences

02:44:45.440 --> 02:44:50.080
[Amit Varma]: happen to be and all of that and sometimes we just really need to shift our gaze and open

02:44:50.080 --> 02:44:54.720
[Amit Varma]: ourselves up to other kinds of writing like you did with you know while reading for unbound

02:44:54.720 --> 02:45:00.320
[Amit Varma]: so um for my listeners and for me can you uh recommend you know as many books as you feel

02:45:00.320 --> 02:45:05.360
[Amit Varma]: like from one to many uh that you feel are important for expanding that gaze whatever

02:45:05.360 --> 02:45:10.640
[Amit Varma]: it is not necessarily from male to female or from indian to japanese or whatever but just

02:45:10.640 --> 02:45:16.880
[Guest]: in general which can help you see the world in a new way um one book that i never get tired of

02:45:16.880 --> 02:45:27.360
[Guest]: recommending is uh sultana's dream and the reason is that it is uh that it is also just good reading

02:45:27.360 --> 02:45:34.640
[Guest]: and um in as a companion to that i would say read sunithi namjoshi's mothers of mayadeep

02:45:34.640 --> 02:45:41.040
[Guest]: they're both fantastical they're both written by feminists they're both about uh uh a place where

02:45:41.040 --> 02:45:49.760
[Guest]: women run things but one is kind of a kind of tongue-in-cheek kind of just pure dream dream

02:45:49.760 --> 02:45:56.640
[Guest]: sequence you know which is almost wishful thinking and the other also tells you the limits

02:45:56.640 --> 02:46:01.840
[Guest]: and and the nature of power itself regardless of who holds it whether it is men or women so

02:46:02.400 --> 02:46:08.400
[Guest]: that i would say that read these two together if you can i would say read baby kamble's the

02:46:08.400 --> 02:46:16.160
[Guest]: prisons we broke uh it is uh baby kamble is a dalit writer and so she also writes from the

02:46:16.160 --> 02:46:21.760
[Guest]: perspective of being a woman in the community she doesn't write from the perspective of being

02:46:21.760 --> 02:46:30.880
[Guest]: only a dalit individual she writes as a woman and and women's place in the hierarchy even there

02:46:30.880 --> 02:46:40.240
[Guest]: i would say read her for sure i would say read uh i she's quite a contentious figure and lots of

02:46:40.240 --> 02:46:45.920
[Guest]: people might hate me for saying this but i think that she continues to remain relevant uh so you

02:46:45.920 --> 02:46:54.720
[Guest]: so you should read the high caste hindu woman uh by pandita ramabai i think um she took decisions

02:46:54.720 --> 02:47:01.840
[Guest]: in her her own life pandita ramabai she took decisions because she had suffered some of that

02:47:01.840 --> 02:47:09.600
[Guest]: orthodoxy and she wrote it as to reveal as an act of speaking up for people who wouldn't and

02:47:09.600 --> 02:47:15.680
[Guest]: she's talking specifically of brahmin women at this time so she's talking about women who are

02:47:15.680 --> 02:47:21.920
[Guest]: quite high up and so when you read baby kamble it's also important to read what high caste women

02:47:21.920 --> 02:47:27.440
[Guest]: go through you read the dalits and then you read what the brahmin women uh slides were like read

02:47:27.440 --> 02:47:34.560
[Guest]: the two together as companion pieces there is this very nice book which is a selection of sarojini

02:47:34.560 --> 02:47:40.800
[Guest]: naidu's uh speeches and letters selection of her speeches and letters which i'm not sure it's in

02:47:40.800 --> 02:47:46.800
[Guest]: print anywhere but if you can find it you should read it because we have always grown up thinking

02:47:46.800 --> 02:47:52.560
[Guest]: of sarojini naidu as a poetess you know and it's kind of romantic and i grew up and i read the few

02:47:52.560 --> 02:47:58.400
[Guest]: of her poems and i was like that yeah this is a little too romantic for me but you read his

02:47:58.400 --> 02:48:08.000
[Guest]: speeches and my god she's a thinker fierce speaker um and and uh is able to articulate

02:48:08.000 --> 02:48:13.680
[Guest]: not only the concerns of women but of a whole country really i mean she was one of the tallest

02:48:13.680 --> 02:48:19.360
[Guest]: leaders of the freedom movement so read her for sure um i'll never get tired of saying this please

02:48:19.360 --> 02:48:26.000
[Guest]: read gandhiji's my experiments with truth uh it's not by a woman but i i do think that one of the

02:48:26.000 --> 02:48:33.120
[Guest]: remarkable things about gandhiji was that it is actually just that it is an experiment with truth

02:48:33.120 --> 02:48:38.640
[Guest]: he does not take for granted that the truth is something stable and that it can never be

02:48:38.640 --> 02:48:43.440
[Guest]: challenged and he challenged it himself in his own life and i think that if he had lived longer

02:48:43.440 --> 02:48:49.600
[Guest]: maybe he would have challenged it even further whatever his existing beliefs were um and i

02:48:50.480 --> 02:48:54.720
[Guest]: and it's also just well written so you should read it for those reasons too

02:48:54.720 --> 02:49:00.880
[Guest]: um you should read ranjeet hoskote's very fine translation of lal derd

